<FIRST>d e BC-Jazz     08-05 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jazz,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Billie Holiday Remembrance Opens `Classical Jazz'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Billie Holiday and tenor saxophonist
Lester Young were remembered by three singers and three tenor
players at the opening of Lincoln Center's third annual ``Classical
Jazz'' series.
   The first of six concerts, each centered around outstanding
figures from the history of jazz, was sold out Friday night at
Alice Tully Hall.
   The performers were Abby Lincoln with Jimmy Heath, Etta Jones
with Houston Person and Shirley Horn with Buck Hill.
   Miss Lincoln, who had the longest set, has an individual timbre,
sounding not at all like Billie Holiday. Her delivery is warm, open
and generous. She seems a balance of tough and vulnerable and she
seems to be giving of herself. She's mesmerizing, pulling the
audience with her into the world of Billie Holiday's songs.
   Heath and each member of Miss Lincoln's trio stretched out in
interesting solos.
   Etta Jones and Houston Person, who have been performing together
since 1976, have their pattern set with his sax providing melodic
fills between her lines of singing. Miss Jones wraps her words and
syllables around the instrumental music, the way Miss Holiday did.
   She also had a trio on stage. Pianist David Braham captured the
imagination.
   Shirley Horn played her own piano accompaniment, with bassist
and drummer. Buck Hill played saxophone with them on every other
song. Miss Horn's approach is lightness. If the other two singers
were airplanes, she was a glider, touching down occasionally. Then
right away, and in no hurry, she'd lift off again.
</TEXT>
