<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0659 08-05 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce Friends and Foes Sought His Favor, Reports Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS two grafs after 6th graf pvs, In its, with NY Times
report; picks up 7th graf pvs, The newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crowd of people seeking favors from former
Housing Secretary Samuel Pierce Jr. included his successor and one
of his most vocal critics in Congress, according to reports
published Friday.
   Four-dozen boxes of documents from Pierce's eight-year tenure at
the Department of Housing and Urban Development contained mounds of
requests for his time or help, the reports said.
   The Washington Post, The New York Times and The Wall Street
Journal, citing documents obtained under the Freedom of Information
Act, report that Pierce became involved in selected cases at the
behest of political associates.
   In testimony before a congressional subcommittee in May, Pierce
said he didn't do special favors for consultants or developers and
had merely instructed subordinates to give personal requests
``careful consideration.''
   Among the documents released to the newspapers were numerous
letters asking Pierce for help or thanking him for the department's
approval of one project or another. The reports did not specify in
every case whether Pierce himself interceded on behalf of those who
sought his help.
   According to the Journal, among those who wrote Pierce were Jack
Kemp, the current HUD secretary who at the time was a congressman
from New York; former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger; Sen.
Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.; and Rep. Barney Frank, a Massachusetts
Democrat who has been one of the most outspoken critics in Congress
of the influence peddling that existed at HUD during Pierce's
tenure.
   In its Saturday editions, the Times said the documents also
showed HUD officials withheld from Congress records that showed the
extent of political favoritism in the award of federal subsidies
for low-income housing.
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., asked HUD in early 1988 for two years of
records on the awarding of the subsidies. The documents show Heinz
was given data only for a four-month period after the program had
been revised to curb political abuses, the Times said.
   The newspapers quoted a letter from James Watt, in which the
former interior secretary thanked Pierce for his support of a
suburban Baltimore housing project that was awarded $28 million in
Section 8 moderate rehabilitation funds in May 1986.
   Watt was paid $300,000 by the developer of the project to help
obtain money from Housing and Urban Development and, according to
previous testimony, had met with Pierce to discuss the project.
   ``Thanks!'' Watt wrote to Pierce on June 6, 1986. ``You are a
man of your word.''
   Asked for comment by the Times, Watt referred to his
congressional testimony last spring in which he said his contacts
with Pierce were proper.
   Pierce faces no charges of wrongdoing, but congressional
investigators have questioned the truthfulness of some of his
testimony. The Post said Pierce could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
