<FIRST>r a AM-Potty-TrainingDeath     08-05 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Potty-Training Death,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>HRS Workers Punished in 2-Year-Old's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three state child-welfare workers were
suspended and a fourth has quit following the death of a 2-year-old
boy whose parents allegedly dunked him repeatedly in a toilet for
soiling his diapers.
   The workers ignored guidelines in returning Bradley McGee to his
mother and stepfather, ignoring warnings that they were abusing the
boy, the Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services said
Friday.
   Bradley died of a brain hemorrhage July 28, shortly after the
HRS workers returned the boy to his parents from foster care.
   Sheryl McGee Coe, 20, and Thomas Edward Coe, 22, both of
Lakeland, were held without bond Friday facing first-degree murder
charges in the case.
   HRS Secretary Gregory Coler said he was upset that the staffers
recommended the child be returned to the Coes despite the abuse
reports and their failure to fulfill an agreement to attend
drug-abuse counseling.
   ``We're not talking about facts that weren't known or somebody
who didn't show up somewhere or that the information wasn't
there,'' Coler said Thursday, the day of Bradley's funeral. ``We're
talking about people not following procedure.''
   Bradley was taken from the Coes' custody in March 1988 after HRS
officials said the Coes had been negligent. He was returned to them
in late May despite the warnings of Bradley's foster parents, the
Kirklands.
   The foster parents said they repeatedly told HRS workers that
they feared Bradley would be in danger if returned to the Coes.
   Three child-welfare workers involved in the case, case worker
Margaret Barber, her supervisor Judy Ross, and subdistrict
administrator Tom McFadyen, have been put on a 10-day, paid leave.
Case worker Shirley DuBoise quit, HRS spokesman Steve Konicki said
Thursday.
   After a closed meeting Friday with angry parents in Tampa, HRS
district administrator Tom Weinberg said HRS has ``got to intensify
the review effort of supervisors in high-level supervision, so we
fully understand the complexities in the case.''
   The parents who requested the meeting have been protesting for
the past several days in Tampa with placards in the downtown area,
criticizing HRS' handling of such cases.
   They also held a candlelight ceremony along the Tampa riverfront
Thursday night on behalf of Bradley and other child-abuse victims.
</TEXT>
