<FIRST>r a AM-F-16Suit 1stLd-Writethru a0796 08-05 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-F-16 Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0796,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Overturns Multi-Million Dollar Verdict</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT time element to Monday, sted Friday;
picks up 3rd graf: `The judgment ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $3.1 million judgment won by the widow of
an Air Force pilot killed in an F-16 jet crash in South Korea more
than six years ago has been overturned by a three-judge federal
appeals court panel.
   The widow, Janet Harduvel of Lutz, can petition the full 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to reconsider the case. If the
request is refused, she has said she plans to appeal to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   Retired U.S. Supreme Court Justice Lewis Powell served on the
appellate panel and wrote its opinion released Monday.
   The judgment was rendered by a U.S. District Court jury in April
1987 against General Dynamics, the F-16 fighter jet contractor, on
the grounds that the plane was defectively designed and
manufactured.
   Mrs. Harduvel's attorney, Howard Acosta, told the appeals panel
the plane had a severe electrical malfunction causing the crash
into a mountain that killed Capt. Ed Harduvel in November 1982.
   Mark Dumbroff, a Washington, D.C.-based attorney representing
General Dynamics, asked for a reversal, contending the crash was a
result of pilot error.
   The panel rejected the argument that there were defects in the
designing and building of the Air Force's newest jet fighter and
overturned the lower court verdict.
</TEXT>
