<DOCNO> AP890805-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Names     08-05 0921</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0954</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Rob Lowe passed out after videotaping two
young women having sex in his hotel room, and the women took the
tape and began circulating copies of it the next day, Rolling Stone
magazine reports.
   Lowe last week agreed to perform 20 hours of community service
to avoid prosecution for allegedly seducing then 16-year-old Jan
Parsons. Her mother drew attention to the video of Miss Parsons and
the girl's friend, Tara Seburt, when she filed suit in May against
Lowe. The civil suit is pending.
   The movie star and Miss Parsons met at a downtown disco during
the 1988 Democratic National Convention.
   Rolling Stone, in its Aug. 24 edition, quoted the dance club's
publicity director, Susan Sullivan, as saying Miss Seburt called
her the morning after the tape was made to tell her about it. Ms.
Sullivan said Miss Seburt told her that when Lowe passed out, she
and Miss Parsons left the hotel room, taking $200 from his wallet,
along with pills and the tape.
   The young women arranged through a friend at a hair salon where
they worked to have someone make copies, the magazine said.
   Lowe, who is filming a movie called ``Bad Influence,'' declined
to be interviewed for the article, and his publicists refused to
comment.
   Rolling Stone said the videotape consists of three segments,
starting with a sex escapade involving Lowe and a male and a female
friend in Paris before he went to the convention. The second
segment shows Lowe's visit to an Atlanta Braves baseball game with
California Assemblyman Tom Hayden and the third shows the encounter
with the two young women, which took place at a hotel on July 18,
1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rolling Stones will bring their
``Steel Wheels'' tour to Syracuse's Carrier Dome for one appearance
to make up for the canceled tour opener in Buffalo, stadium
officials said.
   Syracuse University officials said they expected to sign a
formal contract by Monday for the Sept. 22 concert.
   The canceled Buffalo appearance upset New York rock fans, who
heard the show was called off because of poor attendance at a
concert by The Who at Buffalo's Rich Stadium on July 18. That show
drew slightly more than 30,000 spectators in a stadium seating
89,000 people.
   The Stones' tour, which starts Sept. 1 in Philadelphia, will
take them to Toronto; Pittsburgh; East Troy, Wis.; Cincinnati;
Raleigh, N.C.; St. Louis; Syracuse; Washington, D.C., and Cleveland.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Musicians who quit Lionel Hampton's band because
of inadequate pay are demanding that he rehire them, and a
musicians union tried to picket the band leader's rehearsal space.
   Twelve of Hampton's 16 musicians refused to board an airplane
for Japan on July 25, saying they wanted more money per performance
than Hampton was offering.
   Hampton hired Japanese musicians while he was in the Far East
and hired Americans when he returned last week, said publicist
Chuck Jones.
   Local 802 of the Associated Musicians of Greater New York sent a
telegram to Hampton on Thursday saying his striking members were
ready to come back to work pending negotiations, said union
President John Glasel.
   No answer came back, Glasel said. The union tried to picket
Hampton on Friday but he did not show up at his rehearsal.
   ``Here's a union that got them to strike and now wants to get
their jobs back,'' said Jones. ``He's willing to take them back,
but Lionel's got a new band.''
   Jones said the striking musicians would be the first hired
should the new band members quit, adding that two of the 12
striking members had rejoined the band.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BIG TIMBER, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Tom Selleck, who plays an
American marksman in an upcoming movie about frontier Australia,
won't need a stuntman to hit his marks.
   Selleck proved to be a dead-eye with a black-powder buffalo gun
last week when he visited Shiloh Rifle Manufacturing Co., which is
making three of the guns for the movie.
   He fired about 50 rounds from a 13-pound, single-shot rifle with
a 34-inch barrel, similar to the guns that will be used in
``Quigley Down Under,'' and his first shot hit the 24-inch target
at 425 yards.
   Selleck will play Matthew Quigley, an American rifleman brought
to Australia in the 1800s, supposedly to shoot wild dogs called
dingos. Instead, a landowner wants him to kill aborigines, but
Quigley rebels against the order. The movie will be filmed in
Australia.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 people feted the Queen Mother
Elizabeth on her 89th birthday, and the National Gallery unveiled a
rather dour portrait of her.
   The unconventional portrait showed the Queen Mother without her
customary hat and wearing a simple dress.
   Alison Watt, the 23-year-old Glasgow artist who painted it, said
she didn't want the portrait to look particularly royal.
   ``She always appears fluffy, light, wearing flowing clothes and
I wanted to make her more solid. She has a lot of character,'' Ms.
Watt said Thursday. ``I didn't want her to come across as a wee
waif.''
   A spokesman at Clarence House, where the Queen Mother lives,
would say only that she had seen the portrait. ``We do not issue
statements on silly little things like this,'' he said.
   The Queen Mother, widow of King George VI and one of the most
popular royals, spent about 25 minutes Friday accepting flowers
from children while the Irish Guards played ``Happy Birthday'' and
the crowd joined in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
