<FIRST>r a PM-UnlicensedDropout     08-05 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unlicensed Dropout,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer: Congress Would Be Wrong in Taking Driver's Licenses from
Dropouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress would be making a mistake by
following West Virginia's lead and barring high school dropouts
from driving, said the lawyer for the teen-ager who failed in his
challenge of the state law.
   Kanawha County Circuit Judge Paul Zakaib upheld the law Friday,
saying the government has a compelling interest in keeping children
in class.
   The case involved an appeal filed by 17-year-old Michael Means,
who lost his license when he dropped out shortly after his 16th
birthday.
   The law has drawn national attention, and on Thursday an
Illinois congressman introduced a bill for a similar nationwide
statute.
   Means' lawyer, Christopher Butch, said that would be a mistake.
   Butch said inner-city youths often don't have access to cars and
won't care if their driver's licenses are taken away.
   ``White, suburban kids will go back to school so they can have
the car on Saturday night and go cruising,'' he said. ``Kids in the
inner-city are going to have no reason to stay in school because
they can use the Lexington Avenue subway.''
   Means, whose 16-year-old wife is expecting their first child
this month, lives on the outskirts of Charleston and says he can't
get a job to support his family without driving privileges. He
overslept, Butch said, and did not attend Friday's hearing.
   Means does not have a home telephone and messages left with his
family weren't returned.
   In his ruling, Zakaib said Means was not denied due process
because he was granted a hearing by the state Department of Motor
Vehicles before his license was suspended.
   He also ruled that Means failed to prove he was forced to drop
out of school by circumstances beyond his control, an exemption
provided by the state law.
   Noting that 40 percent of the state's residents have an
eighth-grade education or less, Zakaib said the law is a legitimate
way for the state to persuade students to stay in school.
   ``The failure to graduate or complete a secondary education not
only adversely affects the juvenile, it affects the society as a
whole,'' Zakaib said.
   Assistant Attorney General Bruce Walker, who represented the
state at Friday's hearing, said 400 dropouts whose licenses were
suspended because of the new law returned to school last year.
   The state normally has 5,000 dropouts each school year, but in
1988-89 the number was just 3,400 to 3,500, Walker said.
   ``This ruling establishes that driving is a conditional
privilege and not a basic right,'' said Attorney General Charlie
Brown. ``Further, this law acts as a positive tool in building a
solid foundation for a prosperous and more educated generation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
