<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-PuertoRicoReport     08-05 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico Report,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Statehood for Puerto Rico Could Raise Social Welfare Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Puerto Rico becomes a state, federal
spending for some social welfare programs could rise, a
congressional study says.
   The study, released Friday by Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.,
who requested it, looked at the effects of a proposal for a
referendum on the status of Puerto Rico, currently before Congress.
   The Congressional Research Report analyzed what would happen to
some social welfare programs if Puerto Rico were to become a state;
be granted independence; or receive ``enhanced'' commonwealth
status under which federal grant-in-aid programs could be
consolidated and streamlined.
   For example, replacing Puerto Rico's program of aid to the aged,
blind or disabled with the Supplemental Security Income program
would significantly expand the eligible population, increasing
benefits by as much as tenfold, said the report.
   The study didn't make definitive cost or budget estimates but
looked at the general implications of the alternatives.
   Demographically, Puerto Rico is younger, poorer and suffers
higher unemployment than any of the 50 states, the study noted.
   The programs that would have the greatest impact if extended to
Puerto Rico as a state are food stamps, Supplemental Security
Income and the earned income tax credit, for which benefits are
nationally uniform and not set by the states, the study found.
   Currently, SSI is not available in Puerto Rico. The program,
which is administered by the Social Security Administration,
guarantees a minimum level of cash income to the needy blind, aged
and disabled. Instead, Puerto Rico operates an assistance program
of aid to such people, although disability payments are restricted
to those age 18 or older.
   The U.S. government pays 75 percent of Puerto Rico's assistance
payments to the aged, blind or disabled up to a specified limit,
the report says. In fiscal 1987, Puerto Rico qualified for a
maximum of $12.9 million in matching funds, according to the study.
   But if Puerto Rico were treated like the states, SSI would
replace the current system, providing much larger benefits but
setting much higher eligibility limits, the report says.
Furthermore, SSI would cover disabled children not currently
included.
   If Puerto Rico became a state, the federal food stamp program
would replace its Nutrition Assistance Program, under which
eligible people receive cash benefits.
   All benefits would have to be issued in coupons, and while it is
not clear what the levels would be, they would be higher than in
the rest of the country, according to the report.
</TEXT>
