<FIRST>r w PM-DisasterRelief     08-05 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disaster Relief,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Supports Farm Disaster Assistance Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is embracing a nearly
$900 million package of federal disaster aid for farmers passed by
Congress to cover crop losses this year from severe weather.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter indicated Friday the
president would sign the legislation and he vowed to implement the
relief program ``as promptly and fairly as we possibly can.''
   Passage of the measure by the House and Senate ended weeks of
uncertainty for farm-state lawmakers, who worried they would have
to return home empty-handed for a month-long recess. Now they can
assure farmers that federal relief checks will be available to
cover expenses for the fall planting season.
   ``When our farmers suffer catastrophic loss, whether it's due to
drought, flood or other disastrous weather, we must keep our pact
with those who work the land,'' Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman
of the Agriculture Committee, said before the Senate approved the
measure on a voice vote and forwarded it to the White House.
   The House passed the bill earlier in the day without a recorded
vote.
   In general, farmers can qualify for federal payments if they
suffer crop losses from 35 percent to 50 percent because of
weather-related disasters. The measure also offers payments to
livestock producers facing drought-related feed and water shortages
for their herds.
   Key eligibility and payment provisions in the assistance package
are identical to legislation approved Wednesday by the Senate. The
bill is projected to cost about $895 million.
   ``It seems to me that the final outcome is about as sound as
could have been expected under the circumstances,'' said Yeutter.
   The legislation is aimed primarily at farmers in portions of the
Great Plains and western Corn Belt, which have not recovered from
the drought of 1988, and in the South, where flooding has destroyed
rice and cotton.
   The bill has different eligibility standards for various crops
but in all cases, producers would receive payments designed to
cover 65 percent of their lost income from crop losses.
   In most instances, the projected income levels will be based on
federal crop subsidies or average market prices farmers would have
received had they not suffered losses.
   Lawmakers intend to pay for the relief package with savings from
commodity subsidy programs, which are costing less because of
higher market prices this year from weather-shrunken harvests.
   Last year, Congress approved $3.9 billion in assistance for
farmers hurt by drought. Supporters of this year's legislation said
continued severe weather required another relief package but they
pledged to improve the federal crop insurance program to alleviate
the need for agricultural disaster aid in the future.
</TEXT>
