<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Politics Bjt   08-05 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics, Bjt,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Education Minister, Two Others Compete for Japan Premiership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Minister Toshiki Kaifu and two veteran
politicians from the ruling party today applied to run in next
week's election to choose the third prime minister in Japan this
year.
   Scandals involving bribery and sex have forced Noboru Takeshita
and his successor, Sousuke Uno, from office prematurely.
   While the 58-year-old Kaifu remains the front-runner, some party
leaders complained that he had been selected in backroom factional
manuevers. Offended by those wanting reform pledges, two party
veterans announced at the last minute Friday that they would
challenge Kaifu.
   All three put in nomination papers shortly before the deadline
this morning at the headquarters of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party, which holds a secret ballot Tuesday to elect a
successor to Prime Minister Uno.
   Uno took office June 2, replacing Takeshita, who resigned as an
influence-peddling scandal sent the party's popularity skidding to
record lows in opinion polls. Uno became the target of allegations
he kept paid mistresses, and he decided to step down after the
party lost in July voting for half the seats in the upper house of
Parliament.
   The other candidates are Yoshiro Hayashi, 62, a former welfare
minister, and ex-Transportation Minister Shintaro Ishihara, 56, who
comes from the strongly nationalist wing of the party.
   Whoever is elected to head the party is assured the prime
ministership because of its majority in the House of
Representatives in the Diet, Japan's parliament.
   Kaifu, known as an eloquent speaker, pledged to promote
political reforms to restore public trust in the scandal-plagued
party. In a statement formally announcing his candidacy today, he
also stressed the continuation of Japan's close ties with the
United States and development aid to third world countries.
   ``In order to protect the peace of our nation and the world, I
will maintain the Japan-U.S. security system and continue our
efforts to defend our own country by our own hands,'' Kaifu said.
   Though his career as a 10-term member of the House of
Representatives qualifies him as a contender for prime minister in
the eyes of many party members, he has not served in top Cabinet or
party posts, and his faction in the party is one of the smallest,
giving him little political power.
   On Friday, the large faction led by former Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa decided to support Hayashi, who also belongs to one
of the smallest groups in the party.
   Seiichi Ohta, a leading member of the Miyazawa faction, called
for an open selection process for the next leader and criticized
Kaifu's candidacy as a product of factional maneuvering.
   The ruling party is a collection of a half-dozen major factions
that are differentiated more by personal and financial allegiances
than by policy or ideology.
   Ishihara, a prominent author known for his conservative, often
nationalist views, is supported by some young members of the party
across factional lines.
   He said Friday, ``Politics do not exist for politicians, but for
the country. If we leave the situation as it is now, factionalism
and power politics will continue to prevail.''
   Analysts said Kaifu remained the leading candidate because of
strong backing from factions led by Takeshita and former Foreign
Minister Shintaro Abe, two of the most powerful members of the
party.
   The party's 405 lawmakers and 47 representatives from local
chapters will vote in a secret ballot Tuesday to chose its new
president. The party plans to have the winner elected as the new
prime minister in Parliament Wednesday. A new cabinet is expected
to be announced by late Wednesday.
   The Liberal Democrats have been seeking a strong leader who can
restore public trust in the scandal-ridden party.
   The party's popular No. 2 official, Ryutaro Hashimoto, 52, had
been regarded as a potential contender, but he formally declined to
run Friday, saying his candidacy would have created a further split
in the party.
   Party officials said the new leader will serve only until the
end of October when Takeshita's original term expires. The party
then will hold a new election, they said.
</TEXT>
