<FIRST>r w PM-PlaneEmergency     08-05 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Emergency,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Piedmont Suspends Maintenance Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Piedmont Airlines has suspended two mechanics
who are suspected of having accidentally left wheel chocks in both
wing wheel wells of a jet that was forced to make an emergency
landing in North Carolina.
   The mechanics, whose names were not released, were suspended
without pay pending an investigation by the airline of the
incident, said David H. Shipley, spokesman for USAir Group,
headquartered in Washington.
   He estimated the airline's investigation would take four days
and said, ``Until that time, the full disciplinary actions will not
be determined.''
   USAir Group owns Piedmont and was scheduled to merge the carrier
into USAir today.
   The Boeing 737, with 100 people aboard left National Airport
bound for Columbia, S.C., on Wednesday with a stop in Charlotte. It
was diverted to Greensboro when the crew couldn't get the landing
gear down. No one was injured in the emergency landing.
   Triangular rubber blocks about called wheel chocks, about 2{
feet on a side, are used to keep the plane from rolling while it is
on the ground.
   Phillip Powell, an investigator for the National Transportation
Safety Board, said Thursday a 2{-foot wheel chock had been found in
the left wheel well immediately after the landing and investigators
found evidence _ bent hydraulic lines _ that a chock in the right
well was thrown out during maneuvers to shake the gear loose.
   The two mechanics were assigned to check the plane Tuesday
night, and during that check, said Jay Golden, director of the
safety board's regional office in Atlanta, the aircraft was moved
six times. The chocks were apparently placed in the wells during
one of those moves, he said.
   Ground crews sometimes stuff the chocks in the wheel well while
moving planes, Powell said, a practice he called ``not a normal
procedure.''
   Powell said routine preflight inspection should have included
checking the wheel compartments.
   Pilot Larry Fuda told investigators he delegated the walk-around
inspection to First Officer David Curtis before takeoff.
   Fuda landed the jet on its right main gear, then touched the
nose wheel down before settling the plane onto its left engine and
skidding to a halt on the 10,000-foot runway, a shower of sparks
coming from the scraping metal. Only the left engine, suspended
below the wing, was damaged and the plane is expected to be
returned to service after repairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
