<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0355EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Contras     08-05 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Contras,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Voices Support for Nicaraguan Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush met with leaders of the
Nicaraguan Contras to reinforce his support for their cause on the
eve of today's meeting of Central American presidents to discuss
disbanding the rebel force.
   Contra commander Enrique Bermudez, Contra directorate member
Aristides Sanchez and other leaders told Bush at the 20-minute
meeting Friday that any demobilization must be tied to democratic
reforms by Nicaragua's leftist government.
   ``They said if worse comes to worse, they're prepared to
continue their struggle,'' said one administration official with
knowledge of the meeting.
   Bush said ``he had supported them in the past and would continue
to do so in the future,'' said the official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   According to Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros, Bush told the
rebels he was urging the Central American presidents ``to preserve
the integrity of the resistance'' until the Nicaraguan elections in
February.
   Matamoros said that could mean the forces will remain encamped
in Honduras or move into Nicaragua under conditions negotiated with
the Sandinistas.
   The White House meeting came as Nicaraguan President Daniel
Ortega announced the domestic political opposition had agreed the
Contras should disband. Ortega said he will insist at the
presidents' summit that camps housing 12,000 Contras in southern
Honduras be emptied.
   Matamoros said the rebels support the principles laid out in the
Ortega agreement announced in Managua, but only if democratic
reforms come first.
   The Central American presidents meet this weekend to work on
specifics of their earlier agreement that the rebel army should be
disbanded in return for reform in Nicaragua. The Bush
administration wants clear signs of democratic change before the
Contras have to disband.
   U.S. officials have sidestepped the question of whether that
means they want to keep the Contras together as a fighting force
until the elections.
   ``You can argue over timing, but the answer is ... we feel that
we should not be disintegrating the Contras until there's some
assurance that the Sandinistas are meeting their democratic
commitments,'' said White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater on
Friday.
   Despite Bush's vote of confidence, Matamoros said the rebels
were upset with efforts from ``certain sectors in the State
Department'' to divide the Contras, to speed demobilization.
   On Capitol Hill this week, Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
accused Bush of breaking an agreement with Congress by urging the
Central American presidents not to disband the Contras until after
Nicaragua's Feb. 25 elections are concluded.
   He warned Congress could off the $40 million aid package agreed
to in a bipartisan accord between Bush and congressional Democrats.
   The aid package is to keep the Contras supplied with non-lethal
materials, but also can be used for voluntary relocation of rebels
into Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
