<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Personnel     08-05 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Personnel,</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Announces Key Personnel Appointments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he will nominate attorney
Gene McNary, the chief executive of St. Louis County, Mo., to be
commissioner of Immigration and Naturalization.
   If confirmed, McNary, 53, would succeed Alan C. Nelson, who
recently announced his resignation.
   McNary, an unsuccessful Republican candidate for governor in
1984, has been St. Louis County's chief executive since 1974.
Previously, he was the county's prosecuting attorney and assistant
public defender.
   In other personnel announcements, Bush said Friday he will
nominate:
   _Conrad K. Cyr to be federal circuit judge for the First
Circuit, which covers Maine, Massachusetts, New Hampshire and Rhode
Island, as well as Puerto Rico. Cyr has served as a U.S. district
judge for Maine and became the chief judge for the district in 1983.
   _James M. Strock to be assistant administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency's office of enforcement and
compliance monitoring. A onetime campaign aide to Bush and Ronald
Reagan, Strock has been general counsel at the Office of Personnel
Management for the past year.
   _Reginald J. Brown to be assistant administrator of the Agency
for International Development's bureau for program and policy
coordination. Since 1982, he has been a senior fellow at the Center
for Strategic and International Studies, a Washington-based think
tank.
   _Sidney L. Jones to be assistant secretary of treasury for
economic policy. Since 1986, he has been professor of public policy
at Georgetown University and an associate faculty member for the
Center for Public Policy Education at the Brookings Institution,
also a Washington think tank.
   _James D. Berg to be executive vice president of the Overseas
Private Investment Corporation, which provides risk insurance and
other aid for American firms trying to establish plants overseas.
He currently is with the State Department.
   _Elizabeth M. Tamposi to be assistant secretary of state for
consular affairs. She currently is vice president and partner in a
family-owned development company in Nashua, N.H.
   _William L. Jacobsen Jr. to be ambassador to Guinea-Bissau. He
is a career member of the senior Foreign Service.
   _Christopher H. Phillips to be ambassador to Brunei, succeeding
Thomas C. Furguson. Phillips, of Washington, is former president of
the U.S.-China Business Council.
   _Penne Percy Korth, of Washington, to be ambassador to
Mauritius. She would succeed Ronald DeWayne Palmer. Mrs. Korth was
co-chair of the American Bicentennial Presidental Inauguration,
1988-89.
   _Washington lawyer Stuart Michael Gerson to head the Justice
Department's civil division, to succeed John R. Bolton. Gerson, 45,
is a former assistant U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia
and was a counter-intelligence officer in the U.S. Air Force.
   _Warren G. Leback, 65, to be administrator of the Maritime
Administration, succeeding John A. Gaughan. Leback, of Princeton,
N.J., is a former deputy administrator of the Transportation
Department's Maritime Administration.
   _Forrest J. Remick to be a member of the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, succeeding Lando W. Zech Jr. Remick, 58, of State
College, Pa., currently serves as associate vice president for
research and professor of nuclear engineering at Pennsylvania State
University.
   Bush also announced he would reappoint John Warren McGarry and
Joan D. Aikens to the Federal Election Commission.
</TEXT>
