<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0424EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PrepaidTuition Bjt   08-05 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prepaid Tuition, Bjt,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prepaid Tuition Plan Could Ease Parents' Worries Over College Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a lot of 5-year-olds, Jennifer Wang
dreams of being many things when she grows up. Like a lot of
parents, her father is already worried about paying for her
education.
   ``She wants to be a fireman, she wants to be a nurse, she wants
to be a doctor,'' said Ho Wang.
   With the introduction of the first national prepaid tuition
program, Wang and other parents would have the option of paying now
for their childrens' education _ a hedge against the rising costs
of college.
   Under the National Prepaid Tuition Plan, Jennifer could be
signed up for four years at a college before she can even pronounce
its name.
   ``If I can have the opportunity of locking in the cost now
without having to worry about the rate of return in future years,
that would certainly be one of my considerations,'' Wang said in a
telephone interview from New York, where he works as a high-yield
bond analyst.
   Universities such as Arizona State, Wisconsin and George
Washington have expressed interest in the plan, proposed by St.
Paul-based HEMAR Education Corp., but many others doubt whether it
will ever get off the ground.
   Parents would pay a lump sum into independent investment funds
selected by colleges with the help of HEMAR, which would charge 1
percent annually from the interest on the accounts. This would
guarantee a four-year education, as long as the student was
admitted to the college.
   Wang said he wondered whether highly competitive schools with
tight admissions policies would ever partake in the plan.
   HEMAR President P. Gregory Stringer said he hoped the plan would
be available this fall or winter pending rulings from the Internal
Revenue Service and the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Stringer, a former bank official and assistant director of
financial aid at Yale University, said he envisions at least half
of the nation's colleges, including top schools, signing up within
five years.
   His company, which is affiliated with the Higher Education
Assistance Foundation, a student loan insurer, mailed announcements
about the plan last month to 1,350 schools.
   ``It gives them a recruiting device they didn't have before. Now
they're in a position to recruit students at the age of birth if
they're particularly aggressive,'' said Stringer.
   Stringer said the plan was flexible in allowing students to
select schools other than the ones invested in by their parents.
Such investments could be transferred in some cases, although
parents would receive only their original investment back _ without
interest _ if their children decided not to go to college, or
selected schools not included in the plan.
   ``We worked pretty hard to make sure this plan had value to
colleges as well as consumers,'' Stringer said.
   The National Tuition Maintenance Organization in Ann Arbor,
Mich., is introducing its own prepaid tuition plan, set up as a
taxable mutual fund, to 30 colleges' alumni and supporters this
month.
   Some experts have reservations about prepaid tuition, saying it
would be extremely risky for colleges to participate in the plan.
   Arthur Hauptman, a policy consultant for the American Council on
Education in Washington, an association of about 1,400 colleges and
universities, said it could mean that taxpayers or other students
would have to pay if the invested prepayments don't keep pace with
rising tuition costs.
   Hauptman said a school that hadn't done well in investing the
prepayments might be tempted not to accept some of the children as
students, because prepayment is no guarantee of admission.
   ``I really do think this tension between the admission office
and the business office could become very problematic, where the
economies of the plan may dictate who gets admitted to school,''
Hauptman said.
   State-sponsored prepaid tuition programs exist already in
Michigan, Florida and Wyoming.
   Duquesne University in Pittsburgh pioneered a plan four years
ago allowing alumni parents to pay a lump sum guaranteeing four
years of college assuming the child was accepted for admission.
   But Duquesne suspended the plan last year because of
higher-than-expected tuition increases and lower-than-anticipated
earnings on investments that rendered it uneconomical.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
