<HEAD>Group Claims Man Killed in British Hotel Wanted to Kill Rushdie</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS four grafs with Scotland Yard comment, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously unknown group claimed in a
statement published today that a man killed in a London hotel
explosion was preparing an attack on British author Salman Rushdie.
   Rushdie has been in hiding in Britain since Feb. 14, when the
late Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini said his novel
``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemed Islam and called on Moslems to
kill the author.
   Scotland Yard said a man was killed Thursday as he worked with a
handmade explosive charge inside a London hotel near Paddington
Station.
   The statement from a group calling itself the Organization of
Islam's Mujahedeen did not identify the man, which it said was the
group's ``first martyr.''
   ``Others would follow his example to try to kill Rushdie,'' said
the statement published in Beirut's leading newspaper, An-Nahar.
   ``Henceforth, we warn all those who supported and facilitated
Rushdie's works and helped publish the satanic book to back off
because our hand will reach out for them all,'' the group said.
   The statement called on British authorities to preserve the dead
man's body, saying it would make arrangements to recover it later.
   In London, a spokesman for Scotland Yard said police were
discounting claims that Rushdie was the intended target of the bomb.
   The dead man, the only victim of the Thursday blast at the
18-room Beverley House Hotel, had been staying there for several
days, police said.
   He was believed to have a French passport and be of Moroccan
background, according to hotel records, although his passport had
not been recovered, said a representative of Scotland Yard's press
office, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The dead man's surname
was given as Mazeh, he said, but there was no first name yet.
</TEXT>
