<DOCNO> AP890805-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0553EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NewNewsShows     08-05 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New News Shows,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>New News Shows Premiere to Varied Response, Good Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The premieres of NBC's and ABC's new
prime-time news shows resulted in mixed reviews but relatively good
ratings.
   NBC's ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow'' made its bow Wednesday
to negative reviews for its cheesy special effects, dull stories
and use of re-creations to illustrate some of its stories.
   But the reviews didn't deter viewers.
   Twenty-two percent of the viewing audience opted for ``YTT,''
putting it several points ahead of reruns on CBS (``Wiseguy'') and
ABC (``China Beach''). It did as well or better than the parade of
entertainment shows NBC has tried in the time period, which no one
network has dominated.
   ``Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow'' is getting a three-week summer
tryout, but isn't on NBC's fall schedule.
   The much more highly publicized debut of ABC's ``PrimeTime
Live,'' pairing Sam Donaldson and Diane Sawyer, formerly of CBS,
got good-to-so-so notices. ``Prime-Time Live'' is a weekly series
from here on out.
   Though it came in last in its time period in the Nielsens,
``PrimeTime Live'' was a dramatic improvement for ABC, which has
been unable to make any headway against NBC's powerhouse Thursday
lineup with entertainment programming, such as ``HeartBeat.'' Most
recently, low-rated ``Thursday Night Baseball'' was in the time
period.
   ``PrimeTime Live'' drew 18 percent of the viewing audience. ABC
normally gets about an 11. A rerun of NBC's ``L.A. Law'' got 21, as
did the movie on CBS, ``Outback Bound.''
   Washington Post TV critic Tom Shales praised ``PrimeTime Live,''
saying, ``Network television experienced a welcome electrical
charge last night.'' He called the premiere ``one of the smoothest
maiden voyages in television history.''
   Other critics were less enthusiastic. Walter Goodman, writing
for The New York Times, said Donaldson and Sawyer ``made a
workmanlike team.'' He said, ``No potatoes will be knocked off
their couches,'' but dubbed the premiere ``a respectable effort.''
   Steve Sonsky of the Miami Herald called it ``a good college try,
but not a must-see yet.''
   The New York Post's Dave Bianculli was not impressed at all.
``This is a show,'' he said, ``that started out with more flash
than substance and with more desperation than direction.''
   The critics were pretty unanimous, though, in criticizing the
NBC program, which featured three co-anchors _ Maria Shriver; Mary
Alice Williams, recently acquired from CNN; and local New York NBC
anchor Chuck Scarborough.
   Los Angeles Times critic Howard Rosenberg started out his
review, ``This is a re-creation,'' then constructed a fictional _
and unflattering _ account of what the three anchors might have
been saying when watching the show:
   ``Scarborough: God, I'm a commanding figure. Notice how I speak
deeply and earnestly, my granite chin thrust toward the camera just
so, implying strength and authority. My eyes have never sparkled
like this before. And I'm having such a good hair day, I can hardly
stand it.''
   Rosenberg, like other critics, was especially bothered by the
network news program's use of re-creations, a device identified in
recent months with syndicated news programs of questionable
journalistic integrity.
   ``Don't the news divisions realize they have enough of a
credibility problem without shooting themselves in the knee this
way?'' wondered Shales. As for the program itself, he said, ``If
you called it journalism as entertainment, you'd be stretching both
terms.''
   Concluded Fort Worth Star-Telegram critic Art Chapman, ``NBC was
not any good at putting together a newsmagazine show yesterday,
it's not any better today. It would be foolish to assume they can
do better tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
