<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneStrikes     08-05 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Strikes,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telephone Workers in 24 States Prepare For Possible Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Four regional phone companies faced possible strikes tonight
pending negotiations with unions representing 226,000 telephone
operators, linemen and other communication workers in 24 states.
   Bell Atlantic, NYNEX, BellSouth and Pacific Telesis were holding
separate talks with workers represented by the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers on the contracts that expire at midnight.
   The main differences were over health benefits; each of the four
companies, trying to save on medical and insurance bills, were
trying to get unionized employees to pay a larger percentage of
their medical bills.
   The four phone groups are among the seven so-called Baby Bells
that were created as a result of the 1984 AT&amp;T breakup.
   ``We're in what I would call tough negotiations; they're going
to be negotiating quite heavily in trying to meet that deadline,''
said Vira Milirides, spokeswoman for the CWA in Oakland, Calif.
   Workers may stay on the job past the deadline if the issues are
close to settlement, she said.
   Pacific Bell spokeswoman Jill Foley said the company was hopeful
about reaching agreement with the union, which represents 44,000
workers in California and 6,000 in Nevada, 90 percent of the
non-management work force. Pacific Bell and Nevada Bell together
form Pacific Telesis.
   Milirides said the group wants employees to start paying a
percentage of their health benefits, previously paid entirely by
the company, and is offering wage increases of about 5 percent over
three years, which the CWA says is insufficient.
   Pay ranges from about $228 a week for some operators to $650 for
skilled technicians, Milirides said.
   Similar issues were being debated on the East Coast, where
NYNEX, the telephone company for New York and New England, on
Friday raised its offer on health insurance in talks with the two
union locals representing 60,000 workers.
   But Myles Calvey, president of IBEW Local 2222 in Quincy, Mass.,
said he doubted the offer would avert a strike.
   ``It amounts to about $2 a week,'' he said. ``It's not a
substantial increase. It's not something we can accept.''
   He said many employees joined the telephone company because of
its generous benefits.
   ``The membership is really 100 percent behind us on this one,''
Calvey said. ``Most employees could understand if the company was
in some kind of a financial problem, but they've made record
profits.''
   NYNEX spokesman Bob O'Brien said hundreds of management
personnel are ready to take temporary assignments to maintain
service in the event of a strike, and he predicted that customers
would barely notice, since most telephone operations are automated.
   But Calvey contended that customers would quickly see a decline
in service if the unionized operators, service technicians, linemen
and clerical workers walked off their jobs.
   Other down-to-the-wire contracts were taking place in Atlanta,
where BellSouth was negotiating with the CWA on contracts for
64,000 workers in nine states, and in Philadelphia and Washington,
D.C., involving the more than 52,000 Bell Atlantic employees in six
mid-Atlantic states and Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
