<DOCNO> AP890805-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0556EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Indonesia-Earthquake     08-05 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indonesia-Earthquake,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll From Quake Rises to 116</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue teams have found 19 more
bodies, bringing to 116 the death toll from an earthquake that
triggered landslides in the country's easternmost province, a
government official said today.
   The Social Affairs Ministry official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said rescue workers retrieved the bodies Friday from
under demolished houses and masses of earth in the village of Soba,
in the mountainous district of Kurima.
   Soba was the hardest hit of three villages, including Holuan and
Pasema, nearest the quake's epicenter 219 miles south of the
provincial city of Jayapura, 2,188 miles east of Jakarta.
   The official said workers also rescued 20 injured people who
were trapped in the rubble of mountain slopes that were crumbled by
Tuesday's quake, which measured 6 on the Richter scale.
   The scale is a gauge of the energy released by an earthquake as
measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph, and every
increase on the scale means the motion is 10 times greater. A
magnitued of 6 can cause severe damage.
   Authorities have evacuated more than 700 people from the
stricken area, which has a population of about 3,500 people, the
official said.
   ``Rescue workers still are busy searching for missing
villagers,'' he said via telephone from Jayapura. He could not say
how many remained missing, however.
   An official of the Meteorology Office in Jakarta said an
earthquake with a magnitude of 5.2 shook the southern coast of west
Java on Friday, but that there were no reports of casualties or
damages. He said the quake was centered in the Indian Ocean, 100
miles south of Jakarta.
   In 1981, more than 300 people were killed in Kurima by an
earthquake measuring 6.8 on the Richter scale.
</TEXT>
