<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     08-05 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Hit Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tornadoes touched down in Illinois early today, hours after
thunderstorms rumbled across much of the Midwest.
   Thunderstorms in northeastern Illinois today spawned tornadoes
around Lemont, Orland Park and Joliet, and produced high winds
which downed trees and power lines around Oak Forest.
   Friday night, heavy rains and severe winds ripped the roof off
an apartment complex in Bolingbrook, and caused flooding that left
patients at a Chicago hospital without water or hot food. Doctors,
nurses and ambulance crews worked late Friday to discharge or
transfer about 300 patients from Resurrection Medical Center.
   Elsewhere, severe thunderstorms were moving across Lake Michigan
toward lower Michigan early this morning, producing high winds
which downed trees and power lines.
   Thunderstorms were scattered in southwestern Iowa, northern and
central Kansas, eastern Pennsylvania and eastern New York.
   Showers dampened northern Maine, southern Ohio and central West
Virginia.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms also lingered in
eastern Colorado, southern New Mexico and southwest Texas early
today.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hour-period ending at 2 a.m.
EDT included more that 3 inches at Montpelier, Vt., and 1{ inches
at Rome, N.Y.
   On Friday, thunderstorms developing in the warm humid air ahead
of a cold front in the upper Midwest produced severe weather in
southern Wisconsin. Tennis-ball size hail fell at Coon Valley, and
wind gusted to 75 mph at Milwaukee.
   Thunderstorms also produced severe weather in Minnesota, Iowa
and Kansas Friday evening.
   Golf ball-size hail fell at Owatonna and Rushford in southern
Minnesota and in Delaware County in eastern Iowa. Early evening
thunderstorms in north-central Kansas produced high winds which
downed several large trees and took the roof off a farmhouse west
of Tipton.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
in eastern Kansas, the upper and middle Mississippi Valley, the
Great Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley and the northern and middle
Atlantic Coast; and widely scattered thunderstorms in Florida, the
Gulf Coast, southwest Texas, southern New Mexico and parts of
Arizona.
   Predicted highs: upper 60s and 70s along the Pacific Coast and
across North Dakota and northern Minnesota; in the 100s in the
desert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s elsewhere.
   The nation's temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 47 degrees
at Yellowstone Park in Wyoming to 91 at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 75 fair; Boston 74 foggy; Buffalo 72 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 76 fair; Cincinnati 78 partly cloudy; Cleveland 70
foggy; Detroit 71 fair; Miami 80 hazy; Philadelphia 82 hazy;
Pittsburgh 70 foggy; Portland, Maine 69 foggy; Washington, D.C. 83
hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 67 fair; Chicago 72 thunderstorms; Denver 69
partly cloudy; Des Moines 83 windy; Indianapolis 77 foggy; Kansas
City 80 cloudy; Nashville 78 fair; New Orleans 78 fair; St. Louis
84 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 68 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 75 fair; Anchorage 62 cloudy; Boise 64 fair;
Honolulu 77 fair; Las Vegas 85 fair; Los Angeles 63 foggy; Phoenix
90 fair; Portland, Ore. 65 fair; Salt Lake City 72 fair; San
Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 65 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 73 foggy; Toronto 72 foggy.
</TEXT>
