<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0603EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FiresRdp     08-05 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Brings More Bad Fire Weather to the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Army soldiers set up camp on Idaho and Oregon fire lines today,
just in time for dry, hot weather that had officials worried about
lightning storms.
   Shifting winds pushed a brush fire away from Southern
California's Mount Palomar observatory, which 500 firefighters had
been rushed in to protect earlier Friday.
   Smaller forest, brush and grass fires burned in Nebraska, Utah
and Wyoming.
   More than 21,000 people were at work fighting fires throughout
the West, according to the Boise Interagency Fire Center in Idaho,
the nation's fire suppression headquarters. Almost 225,000 acres
had been blackened or were burning since a rash of lightning storms
in the middle of last week.
   The fire center has managed so far to get people and supplies
where they are needed most, said spokesman Ken Showalter. ``But if
we get another bust (of lightning-caused fires), things are going
to be challenging.''
   About 1,300 soldiers and support personnel from Fort Carson,
Colo., and Fort Riley, Kan., were arriving in Idaho today, said 8th
Infantry Col. Anthony Trifiletti.
   Another 1,300 soldiers from the 9th Infantry, based at Fort
Lewis, Wash., began setting up camp Thursday in eastern Oregon and
on Friday about half of them began training on relatively safe fire
lines before moving to more hazardous duty today.
   The other half of the contingent from the 9th Infantry, which
served on the fire lines in Yellowstone National Park last summer,
was helping firefighters mop up after a fire at Dooley Mountain
near Baker, Ore., that burned nearly 20,000 acres before being
contained Thursday.
   Residents of the old mining town of Warren, about 50 miles
northeast of McCall, in central Idaho, crossed their fingers while
waiting out the 4,244-acre Wangdoodle fire.
   ``They have retardant lines, handlines, dozer lines and
hoselines in there to protect Warren,'' Payette National Forest
spokeswoman Jeanne Felmy said. Still, the fire could ``hook
around'' and make a run for the buildings in the event of erratic
winds.
   The forecast was for a warmer weekend.
   ``We're in an increasing warming and drying trend,'' said Vance
Persing of the Payette forest. ``If we reach the weather we had
several days ago, things could really start popping.''
   Six major fires and at least four smaller fires in eastern
Oregon had damaged about 82,000 acres of the timber and grazing
land, killing cattle and chasing residents from their homes.
   Cool and moist weather this week has helped firefighters get the
upper hand, said Barbara Kennedy, a U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman.
   ``But we're getting back to more normal weather now and that
means firefighters are going to have to work extra hard,'' Kennedy
said from a fire camp in the Malheur National Forest.
   In Southern California, about 2,000 firefighters had contained
60 percent of a week-old blaze in the Cleveland National Forest and
officials couldn't say when they might control the fire, said
Forest Service spokeswoman Rosalinda Ewen.
   The 11,000-acre conflagration 90 miles southeast of Los Angeles
burned to within three miles of the historic Mount Palomar
Observatory, the nation's largest optical telescope, before
shifting away, authorities said Friday.
   Astronomers at the observatory, owned by the California
Institute of Technology, were forced to cease their work and close
the observatory to prevent ash from damaging the telescope's $20
million mirror.
   A fire in northwestern Nebraska had rushed through 4,000 acres
of timbered canyon Friday and up to 30 people were evacuated, but
it was declared contained after two South Dakota National Guard
helicopters dumped fire retardant on hot spots. The fire was near
Fort Robinson State Park, which was ravaged a month ago by a blaze
that charred 48,000 acres.
   Firefighters were close to containing a 60-acre brush fire near
Provo, Utah, this morning.
</TEXT>
