<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0713EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Piedmont'sFarewell     08-05 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Piedmont's Farewell,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Piedmont's Last Day: Aviation's Largest Merger Completed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Piedmont Airlines disappeared today as
the carrier joined with USAir in one of the largest mergers in U.S.
aviation history.
   All over the Charlotte-Douglas International Airport, the
Piedmont logo was being replaced by USAir's red and blue colors
Friday as officials gathered to bid farewell to the airline founded
more than 40 years ago in North Carolina.
   ``The people of Piedmont are justifiably proud,'' said Patricia
Goldman, a USAIR vice president. ``The only way we can prove we're
as good is by doing a good job.''
   As the midnight deadline approached, few vestiges of Piedmont
could be found at the airport that was the airline's major hub,
with 300 departures a day.
   In early 1987, USAir Group, the nation's eighth largest airline
at the time, agreed to pay $1.6 billion in cash to acquire
Piedmont, the nation's ninth-largest carrier.
   On Friday afternoon, officials, city leaders and a few employees
gathered at Gate 12B to say goodbye to the airline founded by Tom
Davis in Winston-Salem.
   The union will create the country's seventh-largest airline with
a fleet of 426 jets and 48,000 employees. The airline will operate
in 36 states, two Canadian provinces, the Bahamas and Britain.
   ``It was inevitable,'' Ms. Goldman said in an interview.
``Neither of us wanted to merge; we both wanted internal growth.
But one of us was going to be bought, and we wanted it to be
compatible.''
</TEXT>
