<SECOND>PM-Hurricane Dean, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0467,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurrican Dean Drifts Northward in Atlantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with position, possibility of hurricane
watch for Bermuda. Picks up 5th graf, `A weakening...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Dean's northward drift away from the
northern Caribbean islands and the southeastern Bahamas prompted at
least a temporary cancellation of hurricane watches and warnings.
   ``Right now it looks as though the hurricane is heading towards
Bermuda,'' said National Hurricane Center meteorologist Jesse
Morre. ``If it continues moving as it is right now, we think a
watch may be needed later today.''
   ``There's just that little dot in the ocean,'' Morre said of
Bermuda, ``and right now, it's heading towards that dot.''
   At 6 a.m. EDT Saturday, the 5-day-old hurricane with winds of 85
mph was centered near 24.3 north latitude and 63.9 west longitude,
about 550 miles south of Bermuda. It was moving northward at 12 mph.
   A weakening of upper atmosphere winds that steer the storm kept
Dean away from the islands Thursday. The hurricane remained
stationary most of Thursday night.
   Earlier reports that said the storm was headed towards Puerto
Rico and the Virgin Islands sparked a rush on stores for supplies.
   Dean, the second hurricane of the Atlantic season, became a
tropical storm Monday night and passed the hurricane threshold of
74 mph winds Tuesday.
</TEXT>
