<FIRST>r w PM-EthicsProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0436 08-05 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethics Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe Set for Three Legislators on Sex Misconduct</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS last graf to give full reference to Hubert H. Humphrey
III.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee can now begin
interviewing witnesses and receiving documents as it proceeds with
preliminary investigations of three lawmakers accused of sexual
misbehavior.
   The committee on Friday announced preliminary inquiries into the
conduct of Reps. Gus Savage, D-Ill., Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens,
R-Ohio, and Jim Bates, D-Calif., to determine if there's ``a reason
to believe'' rules violations occurred.
   Bates denied any wrongdoing. Lukens' press aide said the Ohio
congressman welcomed ``a full and open investigation.'' Savage, who
also has denied wrongdoing, could not be reached for comment.
   If the Committee on Standards of Official Conduct, as the panel
is formally named, decides ``there is reason to believe'' a
violation occurred in any of the cases, it could issue a statement
of alleged violation, similar to an indictment. Later in the
process, the committee could hold disciplinary hearings and
eventually recommend punishment to the full House.
   The House Republican Conference, composed of all Republicans in
the chamber, asked the ethics panel to investigate Lukens, who was
convicted in Ohio on a misdemeanor charge of contributing to the
unruliness of a child. Lukens, who is appealing, was sentenced June
30 to 180 days in jail and fined $1,000 for having sex with a
teen-age girl.
   The committee said the complaint alleged that Lukens' conduct
violated a House rule which states, ``A member, officer, or
employee of the House of Representatives shall conduct himself at
all times in a manner which shall reflect creditably on the House
of Representatives.''
   Jarrell, Lukens' press aide, said the Ohio Republican ``has
already said he welcomes a full and open investigation where his
accusers' motives and the full record can be brought forth.''
   He added that Lukens would be able to bring the committee
information about the credibility of the teen-age girl and her
mother, which was ruled inadmissible for the trial.
   Three House Democrats filed a complaint against Savage this
month, after news accounts said a Peace Corps volunteer complained
the lawmaker fondled her while he was traveling in Zaire.
   The ethics panel said it ``has been presented with complaints
concerning the actions of Rep. Gus Savage while that member
traveled to Africa in connection with his official duties and
responsibilities in March 1989.''
   Since the incident, the State Department inspector general has
sent investigators to collect information on Savage's actions
during official foreign travels, according to a House member who
would speak only as an unnamed source.
   News accounts this week said that when Savage was in China in
1986 as part of a delegation from the House Science and Technology
Committee, he revised his schedule and went to Hong Kong and South
Korea for shopping and sightseeing.
   Savage told reporters two weeks ago, ``I did nothing, that's
what I did. This lie was leaked by the State Department for
political reasons.''
   The complaint against Bates was filed last year by two former
aides, according to published reports. The committee said it ``has
been presented with sworn complaints from two individuals against
Rep. Jim Bates, alleging that they were sexually harassed by Rep.
Bates and that congressional staff and resources were used to
perform campaign-related activities.''
   Bates said, ``I would deny they were sexually harassed and that
the staff and resources were used to perform campaign-related
activities _ at least under my direction.''
   Bates added, ``I look forward to having the matter resolved. It
has gone on for a year without any action. I would like it
resolved. I don't think it warrants a preliminary inquiry, but if
the committee does, we'll cooperate in any way we can.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., disclosed Friday the
Senate Ethics Committee has completed its preliminary inquiry of
his previously revealed book publishing contract _ and voted to
proceed with the investigation. Washington attorney Robert Bennett
has been hired by the committee as special counsel to continue the
probe, Durenberger said.
   Durenberger, whose deal netted him $100,000 over two years,
received income from a publisher who charged ``book promotion
fees'' to groups that sought the senator as a speaker. A complaint
from Minnesota lawyers who backed Durenberger's 1988 re-election
opponent, Hubert H. Humphrey III, accused the senator of
circumventing rules limiting speaking fees members can earn.
</TEXT>
