<SECOND>PM-Secrets-Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Officer Reportedly Suspected of Selling Secrets</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS last graf to CORRECT that Hirsch lists Cleveland Heights,
Ohio, as his permanent residence; SUBS 3rd graf bgng ``Wiggins said ...
'' to CORRECT spelling of Tempelhof.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force officials say they are investigating
an engineering officer in their Electronic Security Command for
what a television network reported is suspicion of selling secrets
to the Eastern Bloc in Berlin.
   Lt. Joe Wiggins, a spokesman for the command in San Antonio,
Texas, said Friday night that the officer, Capt. John Vladimir
Hirsch, has been restricted to Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio.
   Wiggins said Hirsch, who was head of engineering and
installation at the Air Force's electronic security wing at the
West Berlin Templehof Central Airport, was formally placed under
investigation when he returned from Germany earlier this week.
   Another command spokeswoman said the wing collects intelligence
on East Bloc radar and communications.
   NBC News reported Friday that Hirsch is suspected of selling
secrets to the Eastern Bloc while he was stationed in Berlin after
September 1988.
   ``He is not under arrest and he has not been charged with
anything,'' said Wiggins, who would not confirm what the
investigation by the Air Force Office of Special Investigations
concerns. ``There is an investigation that is ongoing,'' he said. .
   According to NBC, Hirsch failed a lie detector test last week in
Berlin.
   The network also reported the Air Force found uncashed
paychecks, evidence of bank accounts totaling more than $120,000,
photographs of Western military installations and other classified
documents in his Berlin home.
   Hirsch also made several unexplained trips to France, Austria
and Italy during the last three years, NBC reported.
   Wiggins said Hirsch came under suspicion during the routine
review of his security clearance.
   ``The investigation resulted from normal security procedures we
employ to monitor security clearance,'' said Wiggins.
   Lt. Erlinda Baker, a public affairs officer with the Electronic
Security Command, said the command works on communications and
electronic combat capabilities, including ways the Air Force
protects its radar from being jammed.
   Hirsch, 33, lists Cleveland Heights, Ohio, as his permanent
residence and has been with the Air Force since 1979, said Baker.
He was born in Prague, Czechoslovakia, and became a U.S. citizen in
1971.
