<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Baffi     08-05 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Baffi,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Director of Italian Central Bank Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former director of Italy's central bank, Paolo
Baffi, has died after a long illness, the bank announced Saturday.
He died the day before his 78th birthday.
   The bank did not disclose the illness. It said Baffi died Friday
night.
   Baffi, one of the major economic figures in postwar Italy,
worked for 40 years with the Bank of Italy, the country's central
bank.
   As its governor from 1975-79, he shaped Italian monetary policy.
He introduced the statistical system still in use today to analyze
monetary and credit issues.
   Bank Governor Carlo Azeglio Ciampi called Baffi ``the critical
conscience'' of the bank.
   Baffi left the bank in 1979 but remained honorary governor. In
recent years, he collaborated with a national commission preparing
a new energy policy. He pleaded for a more cautious approach toward
nuclear energy.
   Funeral services were scheduled Monday.
</TEXT>
