<SECOND>PM-Egypt-US,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Meets U.S. Envoy on Middle East Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak met today with a
senior U.S. official making his first regional tour to explore
Arab-Israeli peace prospects.
   The main topic of John Kelly's talks is an Israeli peace plan
calling for elections in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Elected
Palestinians would then negoiate with Israel on limited self-rule.
   Mubarak received Kelly, assistant secretary of state for Near
Eastern affairs, at the presidential residence. Reporters were
barred, but the meeting was reported by official Cairo Radio and
the state-owned Middle East News Agency.
   The agency quoted Kelly as saying only that the talks dealt with
Arab-Israeli peace efforts and events in Lebanon.
   Kelly arrived in Cairo on Friday from Israel, his first stop on
a three-nation trip that will also take him to Jordan. The trip is
his first to the area after his appointment this year.
   U.S. diplomats have said Kelly's program was confined to talks
with government leaders and he had no plans to meet in Cairo with
representatives of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   During his Israeli visit, Kelly met with 13 Palestinians from
the occupied lands. Though not PLO officials, they support the
organization.
   Israel refuses to deal with the PLO, which it considers a
terrorist group.
