<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BreadStrike     08-05 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bread Strike,0136</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bakeries Open after Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bakeries in this North African nation
reopened Saturday after a 24-hour strike when the government agreed
to discuss bakers' grievances, including demands for a 25 percent
price increase.
   But a government statement also said the work stoppage was
illegal and called on striking bakers to ``show a sense of
responsibility and perform their function for society.''
   When most bakeries went on strike Friday, huge lines formed
outside the few that still were making bread.
   Bakers are demanding an increase in the price for a standard
loaf of French bread from 13 cents to 16 cents. People in this
former French colony generally eat French-style bread.
   Bread is heavily subsidized in Tunisia, and a steep price
increase in 1983 triggered widespread rioting.
</TEXT>
