<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1136EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SavoyHotel Bjt   08-05 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savoy Hotel, Bjt,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Savoy, Rendezvous for the Rich, Celebrates 100 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johann Strauss conducted Viennese waltzes in its
restaurant, Anna Pavlova danced in the ballroom, and Claude Monet
painted his impressionist views of the Thames from a fifth-floor
suite.
   The Savoy, the distinctly English dream hotel, on Sunday marks
100 years of catering to high society, providing an opulent,
discreet and dramatic rendezvous for celebrities, magnates,
potentates and royalty.
   Modeled on the great American hotels of the day, the Savoy was
built by impresario Richard D'Oyly Carte adjoining his Savoy
Theater, home of the Gilbert and Sullivan operettas. From the
outset, it was a byword for exclusivity.
   Princess Elizabeth, later Queen Elizabeth II, first danced here
with Prince Philip. Winston Churchill got the word he had become
prime minister at the Savoy and held War Cabinet meetings in the
Pinafore Room.
   Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower sent his dirty linen from the battle
front. The Maharaja of Patiala had 3,000 roses delivered daily.
Rock singer Elton John left his bath running and flooded three
floors.
   ``Forty years ago, people were excluded mainly because of
money,'' said Stanley Jackson, 78, author of ``The Savoy: A Century
of Taste.''
   ``There's now a more international flavor, an infiltration which
rather destroys the ultra-snobbishness.
   ``The hotel is not snooty or over-introverted. It has kept a
good balance. You've got your dukes and your Sinatras, and they
seem to mix very well together,'' Jackson said in an interview.
   Single rooms go for 140 pounds, or $224 a night, while a suite
can cost as much as 520 pounds, about $832.
   When it opened in 1889, the Savoy was a wonder of the Victorian
age, with 24-hour room service, speaking tubes on every floor, and
67 bathrooms at a time when its most luxurious rival, the Victoria,
had just four.
   Oscar Wilde scorned the built-in washstands, saying that if he
wanted hot water he would ring for it.
   All 202 rooms have buttons marked waiter, valet and maid. The
hotel still insists on its own custom-made mattresses, pure linen
sheets and towels. It keeps separate kitchens on all eight floors
and decorates no two rooms the same, using Art Deco and traditional
English country styles.
   The reservation office keeps 120,000 file cards listing the
needs and idiosyncrasies of regular visitors. A staff of 650
attends to 300 guests, who in an average year order 350 pounds of
caviar, 9,500 sides of smoked salmon, 52,000 oysters and half a ton
of foie gras.
   Requests are almost never too eccentric.
   Frank Sinatra hankered after an espresso machine, so the manager
bought one for him. An Italian marquise required live rabbits to
feed his roommates, a pair of boa constrictors.
   In 1905, a South African millionaire flooded the forecourt to
recreate a Venetian canal, and Enrico Caruso serenaded from a
gondola. The Maharaja of Patiala booked 35 rooms and installed a
silver bathtub and a private elevator in scarlet and gold lacquer.
   U.S. golf champion Walter Hagen started a tradition of driving
golf balls off the roof into a barge on the Thames.
   Asked how long he would be staying, Groucho Marx snapped, ``Till
it stops raining.''
   But a visitor from Chicago who bought a bulletproof vest and
summoned a waiter to test it was politely turned down.
   Weekend celebrations include a birthday ball, a tea party and
fair for 320 disadvantaged children, and a firworks display over
the Thames.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890805-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1143EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-NuclearWaste 3rdLd-Writethru a0494 08-05 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Nuclear Waste, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0494,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Reports 20 Deaths, 1,200 Injured in Nuclear Accidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `The Soviet,' with 1 graf to CORRECT number deaths
reported from Chernobyl. Pick up 10th pvs, `In the...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China today disclosed for the first time that 20
people died and 1,200 suffered radiation-related illnesses in
nuclear accidents from 1980-85.
   The official China Daily quoted Luo Guozhen of the State
Environmental Protection Bureau as saying China needed stricter
control over the handling of radioactive waste and that the
government plans to build more disposal sites to handle the
material.
   Several accidents involving nuclear waste have been reported in
the past, but there have been no official disclosures of deaths.
   Luo told the paper that ignorance about the dangers of nuclear
materials and managers who ignored regulations on handling
radioactive waste had caused radiation leaks.
   In February, the China Daily reported an accident that occurred
last December, when some uranium was lost from a factory and 15
people were exposed to radiation. One man suffered third-degree
burns, the report said.
   In 1986, an article by Zhou Zhumou at the Ministry of Nuclear
Industry's Bureau of Safety, Protection and Health said there were
cases of exposure to radiation when China's nuclear industry
started up in the mid-1950s.
   It said that during the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, when
scientists and technology were ridiculed in political campaigns, a
serious accident took place at a production reactor in northwestern
China.
   Zhou said that about 10 people suffered from overexposure to
radiation in that accident and that another man got uranium
poisoning in an accident in 1973. But he said there had been no
cases of acute radiation sickness.
   The Soviet Union has reported 31 deaths from the 1986 Chernobyl
nuclear accident.
   In the United States, one man died in an accident in 1986 at the
Kerr-McGee atomic plant in Oklahoma and three people were killed by
radiation at an experimental reactor in Idaho in 1961.
   The China Daily also reported that China plans to begin
construction of nuclear waste sites in eight provinces to handle
its growing production of radioactive material.
   Nuclear dumps already have been built in 12 provinces, it said.
It quoted Luo as saying the only major regions that will not have
waste storage sites after 1990 would be Hainan island and Tibet.
   He said the facilities are needed to handle waste produced by
about 1,000 industries and research establishments across the
country.
   Most of China's nuclear waste so far has been generated by the
military, but growing amounts are being produced by scientific
labs, hospitals and non-military industries.
   Adding to the waste storage problem is the planned December
start-up of the Qinshan nuclear power plant in Zhejiang and the
1992 scheduled opening of the Daya Bay plant in southeast China's
Guangdong Province.
   Earlier this year, the paper reported that China was making
plans for its first permanent nuclear waste dumps to be built in
the coastal Zhejiang province and in northwest China.
   The report in February quoted Pan Ziqiang, director of the
safety department of the state National Nuclear Industry Corp., as
saying that so far all of China's nuclear wastes have been put in
concrete basement facilities and those sites only protect the
material for about 10 years.
   Today's report did not describe the facilities being built.
</TEXT>
