<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--HongKong-Police     08-05 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hong Kong-Police,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Getting First Chinese Commissioner of Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This British colony has appointed its first
ethnic Chinese police commissioner to oversee a transition period
leading to Chinese rule, officials announced Saturday.
   Kwan-ha Li, 52, will head the 27,000-member Royal Hong Kong
Police Force, officials said. A police spokesman said he will take
over from Raymon H. Anning on Dec. 1. Anning is retiring.
   China takes back control of Hong Kong in 1997 under terms of an
agreement with Britain. It has pledged to let this prosperous
colony on the mainland's coast remain capitalist for 50 years after
the takeover.
   Li is expected to bring more ethnic Chinese officers into senior
posts. Expatriates now dominate the high-ranking posts, though 98
percent of Hong Kong's population is ethnic Chinese.
   Li was born and educated in Hong Kong. He first joined the
police force in 1957.
   In March 1988, Sir Ti Liang Yang became the first ethnic Chinese
to serve as chief justice of Hong Kong.
</TEXT>
