<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1253EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MermaidsWanted     08-05 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mermaids Wanted,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Attraction Looking For a Few Good Mermaids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEEKI WACHEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mermaids of legend glided
effortlessly through the seas, tempting mortals with their beauty
and grace. It's not so easy in real life.
   At Weeki Wachee Spring, hundreds of young women apply each year,
but few show the needed athletic skills, fearlessness and good
looks to perform far under water at one of Florida's oldest tourist
attractions.
   ``It's tough, there is no doubt about that,'' said Genie Young,
mermaid supervisor. ``We have some strict requirements and only a
few of the `girls' actually go on to become mermaids.''
   Forty-two years ago, the enormous freshwater spring with
startlingly clear water, which extends more than 100 feet down, was
turned into a tourist attraction. ``Mermaids'' wearing skin-tight
suits that taper into a dolphin-like tail fin gulp air through
hoses during the choreographed routines viewed by spectators in a
subterranean amphitheater.
   ``We've done a lot of different things,'' said Ms. Young.
``We've eaten bananas and drank Coke underwater. We've recreated
scenes from movies. One of the hardest things was eating a
sandwich. It gets soggy pretty quick.''
   But for beginners, ``I would say the toughest part is learning
to only take in only about half a lungful of air,'' said Ms. Young,
who performed as a mermaid from 1961 to the early 1970s.
``Otherwise, you will float to the surface.''
   The attraction also features an exhibit of photos of living
mermaids, and a shrine to swimmer-actress Esther Williams. Although
never a Weeki Wachee mermaid, Ms. Williams filmed a movie at the
spring and made numerous guest appearances.
   Despite the specter of discrimination suits, Weeki Wachee
remains extremely selective about its mermaids, who now number 26.
   Several attributes are manadatory: an attractive figure and at
least shoulder-length hair, said Ms. Young. But even most of those
with the right looks get shipped back to land following the
swimming test.
   ``The first thing we look for is if you're afraid of the
water,'' said Ms. Young. ``If you're nervous being underwater,
forget it.''
   Applicants must swim for 30 minutes, and perform simple
underwater ballet and acrobatic moves, such as back flips and deep
dives. The few that remain go on to begin serious training and
instructions in how to use the air hoses and swim in various
costumes.
   They start at $4 an hour and it may take up to a year to pass
the apprentice stage, said Ms. Young.
   Marti Worsham, the veteran mermaid of the staff with 16 years of
swimming behind her, recalls watching the mermaids swim around
large flowers when she was a little girl.
   ``From then on, I always wanted to be a mermaid,'' said Ms.
Worsham. ``I never expected I would one day be the one here the
longest.''
   At the end of a show, after the theater had emptied, a mermaid
scrubbed algae from the windows with a steel-wool pad. A turtle
swam nearby.
   ``This is part of the job the tourists don't see,'' said Ms.
Young. ``Cleaning up isn't part of the myth of the mermaid.''
</TEXT>
