<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Thornburgh'sJourney Bjt   08-05 0946</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh's Journey, Bjt,930</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Downplays Difficulties With Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fresh from stinging defeats in separate
battles with conservative Republicans and liberal Democrats,
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh brushes aside talk about his
difficulties with Congress.
   ``I'm a difficult attorney general, I think,'' a smiling
Thornburgh told reporters last week after the Senate Judiciary
Committee killed the nomination of William Lucas, his choice to be
assistant attorney general for civil rights.
   In making the comment, Thornburgh seemed to revel in the prickly
side of his personality, which surfaces frequently in flashes of
anger when questioned about sensitive issues by legislators or
reporters.
   That anger flared last week when he blamed Lucas' defeat on
``raw politics'' and later accused the Judiciary Committee of
blocking the nominee for failing a ``litmus test'' on civil rights
issues.
   Thornburgh denies his political standing was hurt by the losing
bouts with Democrats over Lucas for the civil rights post, and,
earlier, with Republicans over Robert B. Fiske Jr. to be deputy
attorney general.
   Democrats questioned the qualifications of Lucas, a black
Detroit Republican who has never tried court case but was once
sheriff and later chief executive of Wayne County, Mich.
   Fiske, a prominent Wall Street lawyer with strong legal
credentials, ran afoul of conservative Republicans because of his
role in screening President Reagan's judicial nominees for the
American Bar Association.
   After his public anger cooled, Thornburgh waxed a bit
philosophical about Lucas' defeat last week on a pair of 7-7 votes
by the Judiciary Committee.
   ``I've been in this business a long time. There are some efforts
that are worth fighting for,'' Thornburgh said. ``It's worth the
effort and the criticism that comes from trying to attract good
people to serve in government.''
   But as he prepares to celebrate the first anniversary of his
swearing in this week, Thornburgh is still searching for people to
fill the two important positions at the Justice Department.
   Thornburgh also is also skirmishing with Congress over his plans
to close the department's 14 organized-crime strike forces and
merge them with local U.S. attorney's offices and may be heading
for a confrontation by claiming a right to ignore congressional
objections to his plans to reorganize the department.
   The Lucas battle has raised some questions about Thornburgh's
ability to operate on Capitol Hill, spokesman David Runkel
dismissed any suggestion Thornburgh and his aides misread the
situation.
   ``Our people had every expectation that even on a tie vote, the
committee would send the name forward to the Senate,'' he said. ``I
don't think there was any way for us to predict'' the outcome until
an eleventh-hour Democratic caucus. ``It's clear that they made the
decision late to play hardball.''
   After rejecting a motion to recommend Lucas on a 7-7 tie, the
committee also defeated on the same vote an attempt to report the
nomination to the floor for further action.
   ``This is a journey, you have some things you win, some things
you lose,'' Runkel said. ``The things you lose you learn by them.''
   The Lucas vote last Tuesday came barely a month after Fiske
withdrew from consideration for the Justice Department's No. 2 spot.
   Senate Republicans including Strom Thurmond of South Carolina
and Gordon Humphrey objected to Fiske, saying that as chairman of
the ABA's judicial screening panel he had scuttled some of Reagan's
nominees to the federal bench.
   Thornburgh tried to allay the conservatives' suspicions about
Fiske last spring, telling Congress Fiske had help negotiate an
agreement whereby the ABA consented not to evaluate a judicial
candidate's political or ideological views.
   But Thornburgh's announcement blew up in his face hours later
when the ABA said there was no such agreement.
   An angry Thornburgh then threatened to cut the ABA out of all
judicial screening unless his terms were accepted.
   The ABA and Thornburgh came to terms after a one-month delay,
but that gave Fiske's opponents more time to raise doubts about the
appointment and Fisk bowed out in early July.
   ``Something you learn is timing,'' a lesson that can be applied
to the Lucas case as well as the Fiske episode, Runkel said.
   ``I don't think anybody doubts Lucas would have been confirmed
if the Senate had voted on him prior to all the recent Supreme
Court decisions,'' Runkel said.
   Lucas defended the series of high court rulings on civil rights
that are unpopular with liberal Democrats, echoing the Bush
administration policy that no legislation is needed to overturn
them.
   Lucas's answers disturbed several Democrats on the Judiciary
Committee, prompting Thornburgh later to accuse the panel of
applying too narrow a test on civil rights issues.
   ``I find it somewhat bizarre to expect an appointee of the
president to begin his career in opposition to the president in an
important area of the law,'' Thornburgh told reporters last week.
   Runkel maintained that both Lucas and Fiske were victims of the
``politicization of the confirmation process.''
   Democrats argued that the issue with Lucas was not politics, but
qualifications.
   Despite that judgment, Runkel insists Lucas is a ``solid guy''
who ``will have a position in the administration'' if he wants it.
   The same day Thornburgh lost the bitter fight with civil rights
groups over Lucas, the attorney general helped negotiate compromise
legislation to end discrimination against the nation's 43 million
Americans with disabilities.
   Civil rights lobbyist Ralph Neas, who fought the attorney
general on Lucas, said Thornburgh played a ``very pivotal role
behind the scenes'' forging the compromise.
   ``One of the more fascinating aspect of politics is that today's
adversary can be tomorrow's ally,'' Neas said. ``In this case it
was that today's adversary can be today's ally.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
