<DOCNO> AP890805-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1312EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;LRescue Bjt   08-05 0988</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Rescue, Bjt,960</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Hands Bush Victory on First Major Legislative Initiative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress ended a bitter, two-day parliamentary
standoff early Saturday by adopting a $159 billion rescue of the
savings and loan industry, handing President Bush a victory on his
first major legislative initiative.
   The bill, described as the most important financial law enacted
since the Depression, provides money to close or merge an estimated
500 insolvent thrift institutions and to pay government obligations
incurred in the rescue of 223 S&amp;Ls last year.
   The administration estimates the cost, including interest
payments on bonds issued to finance the bailout, at $159 billion
through 1999. At least half the money will be spent in Texas, where
a combination of lax regulatory oversight and an economic downturn
sent the industry's losses soaring.
   Much of the rest goes to other oil-producing states such as
Oklahoma and Louisiana, and to California and Florida where thrifts
were permitted to enter businesses far removed from traditional
home mortgage lending.
   ``It is without doubt the single biggest bill in the history of
this country,'' said Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, the ranking GOP member
of the Senate Banking Committee.
   In a series of what Bush calls ``never again'' provisions, the
legislation overhauls the regulatory bureaucracy, imposes stringent
financial and accounting standards on S&amp;Ls and quadruples the
maximum jail term for defrauding a financial institution.
   Analysts say the law will touch the lives of everyone who pays
taxes, owns real estate or deposits their money in a thrift
institution or bank.
   The shutdown of sick thrifts paying high interest rates likely
will lower rates to all savers because healthy S&amp;Ls and banks have
raised theirs to compete for deposits, economists believe.
   When the government moves to sell an estimated $300 billion in
real estate inherited from failed S&amp;Ls, the glut of properties
could depress prices in already fragile markets, primarily in the
Southwest.
   Many lawmakers, sensitive to the public perception that they in
effect are giving taxpayer dollars to crooks and con artists, said
the bailout was the only way to protect millions of depositors
whose accounts are federally insured up to $100,000.
   ``We are not bailing out S&amp;Ls, we are not bailing out their
owners or stockholders. We are standing behind our promise to
protect the savers of America,'' said Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Ohio,
the senior Republican on the House Banking Committee.
   Legislators, nevertheless, were reluctant to vote for the
measure. But, about five minutes after midnight, the bill passed
the House by a 201-175 vote. The Senate had approved it less than
two hours earlier in an unusual procedure that avoided a record of
which members voted for and which against.
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the Senate
banking panel, said the rare ``division'' vote, in which senators
stand to cast their ballot, was used as part of informal
arrangement that unsnarled a parliamentary tangle involving
unrelated measures. Riegle said the bill would have passed with
about 70 votes had a roll call been taken.
   The S&amp;L bill, which runs to nearly 1,000 pages, is the first
major piece of legislation initiated by Bush. Only two weeks after
taking office, the president called on Congress to act in 45 days
to stem a financial emergency inherited from the Reagan
administration. It took Congress six months, but lawmakers gave
Bush substantially what he wanted.
   The crisis had been building for years, but was little discussed
in government outside of regulatory agencies and Congress' banking
committees. Bush, and his Democratic opponent, Michael Dukakis,
virtually ignored the issue during the 1988 election campaign.
   The final dispute holding up passage had little to do with the
S&amp;L problem and much to do with the political struggle between
Congress and the administration over balancing the federal budget
deficit.
   Bush wanted to finance $50 billion of the program through a new,
quasi-private agency, thus keeping S&amp;L spending from ballooning the
federal budget deficit, which in turn would trigger automatic,
across-the-board spending cuts under the Gramm-Rudman deficit
reduction law.
   Democrats, trying to pressure Bush into reneging on his ``no new
taxes'' pledge, wanted to embarrass the administration with
climbing annual deficits. They would have avoided the spending cuts
by simply waiving Gramm-Rudman.
   The White House claimed that would have set a precedent opening
the way for a congressional spending spree on other projects.
Democrats said their plan saves billions of dollars in interest
costs because the government would borrow bailout money with
regular Treasury debt.
   On Thursday morning, Bush threatened to veto the S&amp;L bill unless
it included his funding plan. Shrugging off the threat, the House
voted 221-199 to adopt the Democratic proposal. The Senate,
however, fell six votes short of the 60 needed to waive
Gramm-Rudman and sent the legislation back to a conference between
the two chambers.
   With the participation of Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady
and Budget Director Richard Darman, congressional negotiators
worked out a compromise late Thursday night.
   Twenty billion dollars will be raised this year under the
Democratic plan, inflating the deficit to about $168 billion, the
highest in three years. The remaining $30 billion will be raised
under the president's scheme, keeping the spending out of the
deficit in 1990 and 1991.
   On Friday, opposition to the pact from two influential House
chairmen, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., of the Ways and Means
Committee, and Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., of the Budget
Committee, jeopardized final passage.
   ``There is a time to fold and there is a time to be bold,''
Rostenkowski said, urging Democrats hold out for their plan through
the early morning hours.
   But he and other speakers were interrupted with periodic shouts
of ``Vote! Vote!'' from members anxious to follow their 51
colleagues who had already gone home.
   In the end, the lure of summer vacation proved more powerful.
Enough Democrats folded to allow Republicans to pass the compromise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
