<DOCNO> AP890805-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-Glance     08-05 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Glance,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highlights of S&amp;L Bill Adopted By Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;L Rescue Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress early Saturday voted final passage of
a landmark savings and loan bill described as the most significant
piece of financial legislation in 50 years. Here are the highlights
of the bill:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   According to the latest Bush administration estimate, the
bailout will cost $159 billion through 1999. That includes $60.5
billion to meet government obligations incurred in the rescue of
223 S&amp;Ls in 1988, $74.2 billion to close or merge more than 500
additional S&amp;Ls and $24.4 billion for the government's share of
interest on bonds sold to help pay for the bailout. Congress'
General Accounting Office estimates the cost, with interest over 30
years, at $285 billion. Of that, $157 billion will come from the
taxpayers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CAPITAL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In the most important reform in the bill, S&amp;L owners, 120 days
after enactment, will be required to invest more of their own
capital in their institutions. The provision, aimed at discouraging
risky investments, requires owners to back every $100 they lend
with $1.50 in tangible capital. By 1995, the standard will be $3.
Many of the accounting loopholes that allowed S&amp;L owners to avoid
capital requirements have been closed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INSURANCE PREMIUMS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Both S&amp;Ls and commercial banks will pay more for the government
deposit insurance that protects savers' accounts up to $100,000.
Bank premiums will jump from 8 cents per $100 to 15 cents. S&amp;L
premiums will rise from 20.8 cents to 23 cents. Analysts believe
some of the expense will be passed on to savers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FINANCIAL STANDARDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The bill pushes S&amp;Ls back into home mortgage lending and out of
risky investments such as speculative commercial real estate
projects and junk bonds. Thrift institutions are required to raise
the level of housing and housing-related loans in their portfolios
to 70 percent, up from the current 60 percent requirement. S&amp;Ls
currently involved in risky ventures will have five years to phase
out their investments. After that, they can invest in those areas
only through separately capitalized affiliates that involve no risk
to insured deposits.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUREAUCRACY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The lead S&amp;L regulatory agency, the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board, is being dismantled. Its regulatory divisions will be
transferred to a new agency within the Treasury Department. The
fund insuring S&amp;L deposits moves to the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., which already insures commercial banks. The 12 regional
Federal Home Loan Banks, which are owned by the industry, remain
independent. They will lose their regulatory power but continue to
provide low-cost financing to S&amp;Ls.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOUSING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The industry-owned regional Federal Home Loan Banks will be
required to earmark $50 million a year, increasing to $100 million,
to help finance housing for poor people.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANTI-DISCRIMINATION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Banks and S&amp;Ls will have to disclose reports from federal
regulators evaluating how well they serve poor and minority
neighborhoods. Mortgage lenders will be required to collect and
disclose data on the race, sex and income level of customers and
loan applicants.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REAL ESTATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A new agency, the Resolution Trust Corp., will be created to
sell more than $300 billion in real estate now owned by bankrupt
S&amp;Ls. The FDIC will do the work, overseen by a board headed by the
treasury secretary. The government will be required to give housing
authorities and non-profit agencies first chance to buy housing
from the S&amp;Ls. Some fear the massive property sales will further
damage real estate markets in already-depressed oil-producing
regions.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANTI-FRAUD</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is getting $75 million a year for the
next three years to uncover and prosecute fraud at both S&amp;Ls and
banks. It is directed to establish a special fraud task force in
Texas, where most S&amp;L problems are centered. Maximum fines for
financial institution fraud are being raised from $5,000 a day to
$1 million and the maximum jail term from five years to 20 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
