<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru a0524 08-05 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miners Walk Out Again in Vorkuta but Decide to Return to Work Sunday</HEAD>
<HEAD>LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with miners agreeing to return to work,
quotes. Pickup 8th, ``Premier Nikolai ...'' ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miners in the far northern Vorkuta region
walked off their jobs Saturday but then agreed that government
concessions are generous enough to keep them at work at least until
next year, official reports said.
   The Tass news agency said thousands of miners shut down 11 of 13
mines in the coal-rich Pechora field north of the Arctic Circle but
agreed to start working again at midnight after officials explained
concessions included in a government decree.
   ``At a joint conference, representatives of mines and
enterprises of the town unanimously decided to stop the strike
until Jan. 1, 1990, and to start working from midnight,'' state TV
reported. It did not say what would happen after the first of the
year.
   Workers decided Friday to stay off the job until they received
the full text of a government decree that officials say fulfills
promises made to end a wave of strikes last month.
   The promises included bonuses for night work and for miners who
use dangerous equipment, and better pension and overtime benefits.
The government also made general pledges to improve housing and end
shortages of food and consumer goods.
   A spokesman at the Organizational Department of the local
Communist Party headquarters said in a telephone interview that
Alexander Tsuryupa, a director of the state enterprise that
operates all 13 mines, brought a copy of the decree from Moscow,
1,100 miles to the southwest, and explained it to the workers
Saturday.
   The miners then held a closed meeting to decide whether to go
back to work, said the official, who declined to identify himself.
   ``Emotions have stabilized and now there are no outbursts,'' he
said.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev called last month's
strikes by hundreds of thousands of coal miners the greatest trial
of his 4{ years in power. He sympathized with the workers but urged
them to return to their jobs.
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov told the official media Friday that
the settlement with the miners would cost about $3.2 billion.
   He said it would be difficult for the government to come up with
the money and told other workers that if they strike they will hurt
only themselves.
   ``If we follow the road of strikes, no one will benefit from it
and low-paid sections of the population will be hit first,'' he
said in a television interview.
   The Vorkuta miners first struck July 19, several days after
thousands of miners in other parts of the Soviet Union already had
walked out. They demanded better living and working conditions and
that the government pay more attention to the problems of workers
in the far north. They returned to work after about a week.
   Workers in the Kuzbass area of Siberia, where the strikes began,
conducted a two-hour warning strike Thursday because they said the
government is not living up to its promise to shut down a
hydroelectric project the miners say is damaging the environment.
</TEXT>
