<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1422EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Algeria     08-05 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Algeria,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Algeria: Skilled Broker in Hostage Crises</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Moslem Arab country has combined
strong revolutionary credentials, good Western contacts, and deft
diplomacy to forge a reputation as a successful mediator of hostage
crises.
   It counts among its negotiating coups the release in January
1981 of Americans who were held hostage at the U.S. Embassy in Iran.
   This North African country's envoys are once again playing the
role of mediator: this time in the hostage crisis in Lebanon.
   Algeria is no stranger to that country's turmoil. Though
Algeria's exact role never has been spelled out, French officials
thanked the nation publicly after French hostages were released by
pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon in 1987-1988.
   ``We have a skill that we put at the disposal of the
international community,'' the Algerian ambassador to Washington,
Mohammed Sahnoun, told reporters in April 1988. He spoke after
Shiite Moslem hijackers of a Kuwaiti jetliner gave up the plane in
Algeria and were apparently allowed to escape.
   Sahnoun said he could not provide details of the agreement
because it would break Algeria's word to the hijackers and damage
its chances of helping in such situations in the future.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain and former Secretary
of State George Shultz criticized the decision to release the
Kuwaiti hijackers, who killed two passengers.
   In response, Algeria rejected what it called an effort ``to
fling discredit on an action which saved precious human lives from
murderous violence.''
   Perhaps the most prominent Algerian success came Jan. 20, 1981,
when American hostages held 444 days in Tehran stepped off an
airliner at the Algiers airport.
   Iran and the United States had cut a deal _ after months of
mediation by Algerian diplomats.
   ``A happy ending might change the American view that we are
communists,'' a senior Algerian official said at the time.
   After a war with France that led to independence in 1962,
Algeria pursued socialist policies and shaped close ties with the
Soviet Union and radical Moslem groups.
   While Algeria is often in clear sympathy with the aims of
radical organizations, it has steered clear of supporting terrorist
tactics.
   In October 1977, Algerian officials negotiated at the foot of a
Japanese DC-8 hijacked by guerrillas from a group known as the Red
Army. The Algerians helped win freedom for hostages in exchange for
a $6 million ransom and the release of six of the militants'
comrades in Japanese jails.
   In this case, the hijackers also were apparently allowed to
leave Algeria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890805-0090 </DOCNO>
