<FIRST>r i AM-Hezbollah-Hostages     08-05 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hezbollah-Hostages,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Iranian Group Names Five It Wants Freed From Israeli Jails</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pro-Iranian extremist group Hezbollah
on Saturday named five Palestinians and Lebanese whom it said
Israel should release along with an abducted Moslem cleric.
   Hezbollah also denied holding any negotiations on a possible
prisoner exchange with Israel.
   The Shiite Moslem organization was reacting to Israel's July 28
abduction from Lebanon of Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid. Israel has said
it will trade the cleric, whom it links to terrorism, and up to 60
other Shiites for three Israeli prisoners and the 17 foreigners
held in Lebanon.
   Hezbollah said the abduction of Obeid has ``blocked chances for
a swap,'' but it also said Israel should ``free Sheik Obeid first.''
   One Shiite group in Lebanon claimed it killed a U.S. Marine it
held hostage in retaliation for Obeid's abduction. A second group
threatened to kill another American but later said it had issued a
reprieve.
   Hezbollah's statement came the same day a ranking Maronite
Catholic bishop crossed into Beirut's Moslem sector to meet with
Hezbollah's spiritual guide, Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah.
Bishop Khalil Abi-Nadir told reporters he carried a message from
Pope John Paul II asking that the body of the Marine, Lt. Col.
William Higgins, be returned to his family.
   Hezbollah has demanded that Israel release the cleric, in
addition to Palestinians jailed during the anti-Israeli uprising in
the occupied lands and captured guerrillas.
   The statement issued Saturday listed the five detainees as the
``uprising heroes'' Nidal Zaloum, Itaf Alyan and Abdul-Hadi
Suleiman Ghanem and the ``Lebanese resistance heroes'' Anwar Yaseen
and Soha Bishara.
   It quoted an unidentified ``responsible source'' in Hezbollah as
saying: ``We are as eager to obtain (their) release as much as we
are eager to obtain the release of the detainees who belong to the
sons of Hezbollah.''
   Zaloum stabbed two Israelis to death in Jerusalem, and Ghanem
carried out an attack on a bus. Ms. Alyan was arrested before she
could carry out a bombing in August 1987.
   Yaseen was arrested and accused of preparing an attack on
Israel's self-designated security zone in south Lebanon.
   Ms. Bishara shot and wounded Maj. Gen. Antoine Lahd, commander
of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army militia, on Nov. 7 in
south Lebanon.
   Despite public disclaimers, Hezbollah is widely believed to be
the umbrella for Shiite Moslem factions holding most of the 16
Western hostages in Lebanon.
   Hezbollah said lists of other prisoners it wants released will
be prepared within days and presented to the Red Cross.
   The chief delegate of the International Committee of the Red
Cross in Lebanon, Michel Dufour, told The Associated Press on
Saturday that his group had not been approached.
</TEXT>
