<FIRST>r a AM-HigginsScholarship     08-05 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Higgins Scholarship,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pledges Pour in for Fund Honoring Hostage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scholarship fund started for Lt. Col.
William Higgins' daughter has gotten an unexpectedly widespread
response, with $10,000 in pledges, organizers said.
   ``The people who can't afford to give are giving,'' said Pat
Mullen, a lawyer who served with Higgins in the Marines in the late
'60s. ``The most important ones are the $5 and $10 contributors,
who are not Marines.''
   Higgins, 44, was in Lebanon serving as part of an international
peacekeeping force when he was taken hostage in February 1988.
   On Monday, his captors released a videotape that seemed to show
Higgins hanging from a noose, saying he had been killed in
retaliation for the Israelis' seizure the previous week of a Shiite
Moslem cleric. U.S. officials have speculated that Higgins actually
was killed some time earlier.
   Mullen and Dallas businessman Schuyler Page, another former
Marine, originally intended to gather enough money to assist
Higgins' 19-year-old daughter, Christine, a student at James
Madison University in Virginia.
   But Mullen said Friday that the total had already hit $10,000
and may grow large enough to set up an endowment to help other
dependents of people killed during military service.
   ``With the public response, I don't think it's inconceivable
that we can raise over $100,000, which will allow us to do more in
Colonel Higgins' name,'' he said.
   Page and Mullen were classmates with Higgins in an officer
training course. and after it ended in November 1967, they served
in Vietnam.
   Defense Department spokeswoman Maj. Kathy Wood said people who
know Higgins continue to hope that he is not dead. She said Miss
Higgins learned of the scholarship fund Friday and was touched by
the effort.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Contributions can be sent to: Lt. Col. W.R. Higgins Scholarship
Fund, Texas Commerce Bank, P.O. Box 550, Austin, Texas 78789.
</TEXT>
