<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Floods     08-05 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Floods,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>100,000 Marooned In Floods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100,000 people were marooned,
many on roofs, after rivers burst their embankments and caused
floods that killed at least 150 people in the last two weeks,
officials and news reports said Saturday.
   The torrential rains ended Thursday, and officials said river
embankments had burst at 17 places, washing away mud-and-straw
houses in at least 100 villages. They said floods had affected some
250,000 people.
   The area most severely hit was the tea-growing Zakiganj area in
Sylhet district, 120 miles northeast of Dhaka, a Relief Ministry
official said.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said at least
10 people died of diarrhea in Zakiganj in the last three days. At
least 1,000 others were affected by the disease caused by dirty
drinking water, he said.
   News reports reaching Dhaka said at least 150 people died in the
Zakiganj area as a result of the rains in the past two weeks.
   The government has sent 12 medical teams to Zakiganj.
   ``The situation is quite alarming. We are trying our best to
evacuate the marooned people, but we don't have enough
speedboats,'' said an official who visited the area Friday.
   Many people were stranded on roofs with floodwaters around them,
and some had built makeshift bamboo platforms, he said.
   ``Many people have grain, but they have no dry place to cook,''
he said.
   The Flood Forecasting Center said water was receding in the
Kushiara River in Zakiganj but was still above the danger level.
   Flooding is an annual problem in this impoverished nation of 110
million. More than 1,400 people were killed last year in floods
that submerged three-fourths of the country.
</TEXT>
