<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1459EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TroubledMayor Bjt   08-05 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Troubled Mayor, Bjt,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Summer L.A. Mayor Tom Bradley Lost His Teflon</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a few moments, a Beverly Hills
fund-raising dinner looked like the good old days before Mayor Tom
Bradley's fifth term turned into a tangle of investigations that
cut into his reputation of integrity.
   As Bradley took the podium last week in a hotel ballroom, 800
organized labor activists stood and applauded. Pocket cameras
flashed. Busboys turned from clearing tables to catch a look at the
mayor.
   The 71-year-old Bradley was in characteristic form, tall and
athletic like the UCLA track star he used to be, his voice deep and
monotone as he delivered a speech praising organized labor.
   The mayor gave no clue of the problems dogging the fifth term he
won in April _ the allegations of conflict of interest and
influence peddling, accusations of coverup and speculation that he
may resign.
   City Attorney James Hahn is probing, among other things, the
mayor's ties to two financial institutions that paid Bradley while
doing business with the city.
   Bradley, who denies any wrongdoing, said Friday he has
established an account for supporter contributions to cover his
legal expenses.
   Hahn's probe, expected to be completed by mid-September, hangs
over City Hall.
   ``All conversations begin with a discussion of this. It's the
first thing people say as they shake your hand,'' said Joy Picus, a
member of the City Council.
   Shortly before the election, newspaper reports said the city
treasurer directed the deposit of $2 million in a bank paying
$18,000 to the mayor to act as adviser.
   The deposit was made in Far East National Bank on the day the
mayor called Treasurer Leonard Rittenberg, and one day after the
mayor spoke with the bank president about the city's failure to
renew a $1 million certificate of deposit.
   Rittenberg denied the mayor influenced him and the mayor denied
any wrongdoing. Bradley returned the $18,000, and made it through
the election, barely avoiding a runoff.
   But questions persisted.
   An official in the treasurer's office testified before a City
Council committee that his two bosses, including Rittenberg, tried
to cover up the mayor's role in the Far East deposit, an allegation
Rittenberg denies.
   The official, George Sehlmeyer, said a city form was doctored so
that the notation ``per the mayor'' next to the Far East deposit
record was covered with correction fluid.
   ``I was stunned to hear the mayor was even involved,'' said
Sehlmeyer.
   Other probes of Bradley include:
   _ A city-funded Africa task force whose executive director,
Juanita St. John, is involved in a lucrative real estate deal with
the mayor.
   Ms. St. John has been charged with misdemeanor failure to comply
with a subpoena after refusing to turn over documents on $180,000
in task force checks written to herself, or for ``cash.''
   _ The Justice Department is looking into whether investment
banking firm Drexel Burnham Lambert gave the mayor favorable
treatment in stock deals in exchange for favored treatment by the
city.
   _ The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission is reviewing
whether Bradley's stock and bond trades were tainted by insider
trading.
   Walter Zelman, executive director of the political watchdog
group Common Cause, said that Bradley's acceptance of money from
Far East was ``pretty unusual and pretty blatant and a really
serious mistake.''
   The mayor also was hired by Valley Federal Savings &amp; Loan to act
as adviser while that institution was doing business with the city.
   If Bradley did use his influence to direct city dollars to the
institutions, he could face criminal charges, said Zelman.
   But until the city attorney completes his investigation, many
city officials and business leaders refuse to speculate about the
mayor.
   ``Everyone is entitled to a fair hearing,'' said Councilman Nate
Holden, who opposed Bradley in the last election. ``You don't jump
up and down on a guy just because he's been accused.''
   But even the mayor's supporters said they have found it hard to
believe he would work for a bank that was doing business with the
city.
   ``In all the years I've known him, I've never known him before
these matters came up to be anything but completely honest and
forthright,'' said Councilwoman Joan Milke Flores. ``In that way
it's a surprise that he would even allow these things to happen.''
</TEXT>
