<FIRST>r i AM-MouseFever     08-05 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mouse Fever,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eleven Die of Viral Infection Known As ``Mouse Fever''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven people have died in central
and eastern Yugoslavia in June and July of a viral infection, and
at least 140 other people have been hospitalized because of the
illness, news reports said Saturday.
   The daily Politika Ekspres said three people died in Belgrade
hospitals out of a total of nine diagnosed there as having the
infection. Two people died in the town of Pec in the southern
province of Kosovo, where several were reported afflicted with the
virus known as ``mouse fever.''
   Last month, the national news agency Tanjug reported a total of
six dead and 126 hospitalized in central Yugoslavia from the
disease, which is spread by field mice and other small rodents and
their parasites.
   The symptoms include high fever, back and abdominal pains and
redness of the face and eyes.
   Doctors advised people to wash produce, berries and mushrooms
carefully and take precautions when outdoors.
   Experts have said the mortality rate in patients afflicted with
the disease can be as high as 10 percent. They say there is no
efficient drug or vaccine to treat it.
   Earlier press reports said the first cases this year of the
disease appeared in May in the central republic of
Bosnia-Hercegovina. There have been outbreaks of the disease in
Yugoslavia also in 1961, 1967, 1968 and 1986.
</TEXT>
