<FIRST>r i AM-Angola     08-05 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Both Sides in Angolan War Report Cease-fire Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops and U.S.-backed rebels
accused each other Saturday of breaking a June 24 cease-fire in
Angola's civil war, and confusion surrounded the future of talks
aimed at ending the conflict.
   An Angolan armed forces statement said three rebel battalions
attacked government soldiers in central Bie province. The statement
did not mention casualties but said the rebels used South
African-supplied artillery in the action.
   The ANGOP state news agency quoted military sources as saying 16
people died in other rebel attacks around the country.
   For the first time since the cease-fire, the army said it
engaged rebel forces, claiming government soldiers killed two
guerrillas who attacked barracks in northern Kwanza Norte province,
according to ANGOP.
   A statement from the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola accused the government of a number of
attacks in central Angola, including one in which a civilian was
killed.
   Both sides repeatedly have accused each other of attacks since
shortly after the truce, which was reached June 22 in Gbadolite,
Zaire, between Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and rebel
leader Jonas Savimbi.
   The agreement charged Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko with
mediating peace talks. The first round of negotiations between the
warring sides, in Kinshasa, Zaire, were abandoned July 1 after dos
Santos accused the rebels of breaking the truce. Resumed talks
ended July 22 when rebel delegates asked for time to consult
Savimbi in his southeast Angolan stronghold of Jamba.
   The talks were to start again July 31. But they were postponed
after 42 people died when a military transport plane was shot down.
The government accused rebels of downing the plane. The rebels said
the aircraft was hit by fire from government forces.
   Government sources on Tuesday said dos Santos would meet Mobutu
for talks to put the peace process back on track, but no date has
been announced.
</TEXT>
