<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     08-05 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghans Blame U.S., Soviet Union For Rocket Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joginder Singh grabbed a piece of
shrapnel from a rocket that tore through his aunt's house Saturday,
wounding his three young cousins, and demanded to know why the
United States and the Soviet Union were allowing innocent Afghans
to be hurt and killed.
   Singh's relatives and the two young children of a neighbor
playing in the front yard were among the latest victims of the
rocketing of Kabul, an almost daily event since late June.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said 13 rockets
pounded the capital Saturday, wounding eight people. During and
after his briefing, at least four more rockets fell, their
distinctive boom heard across much of the city.
   Amani said the rockets Saturday hit many areas but were
concentrated around Kabul's main grain silo, where several hundred
trucks loaded with wheat from the Soviet Union were waiting to be
unloaded.
   The rockets missed the silo, but one tore into the ground about
a yard in front of a watchtower on its perimeter, breaking the
tower's windows and those of nearby houses.
   For the last four or five months, Amani said, U.S.-backed
guerrillas fighting to oust the Soviet-backed government have been
trying to starve this city by cutting roads and preventing food
deliveries.
   ``Now that they can't cut the roads and all these supplies are
coming to the city, their attack is to destroy what has already
been delivered. It is their aim to impose starvation,'' he said.
   The Singh family house is about 1{ miles from the silo.
   The home's metal roof was torn off, and a rocket's path could be
traced through two-foot-wide holes down to the ground floor. On the
second floor, where Singh said his 16-year-old cousin had been
ironing, a pile of newly pressed sheets, stained with blood, lay in
the rubble amid twisted fragments of shrapnel and the dusty iron.
   The windows in a primary school next to the two-story house were
shattered.
   ``If the school had been open, God knows how many students would
have been killed,'' Singh said. The government has extended the
summer holiday because of rocket attacks.
   ``We think this is a policy of the United States and the Soviet
Union. They are dividing the world ... and they are dividing Afghan
brothers, the Afghan country,'' said Singh, an Afghan of Indian
descent.
   ``If the government cannot protect the people, they have no
right to rule. And the United States and the Soviet Union, why are
they doing this to innocent people? What have we done?,'' he asked.
   According to U.N. sources, 281 people were killed and 745
injured in rocket attacks and a car bombing in Kabul from June 25
to Aug. 1. Virtually all were civilians.
   A three-day lull last week was broken Friday when 19 rockets
killed two people and injured nine, Amani said.
   The rebels, who call themselves mujahedeen or Islamic holy
warriors, have claimed responsibility for some rocketing but insist
they aim at military targets and blame the government for hitting
civilian targets. The government denies it.
   Amani accused U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar of
not doing enough to stop ``gross violations'' by the United States
and Pakistan of U.N.-mediated accords that were supposed to stop
U.S. arms supplies to the mujahedeen and Soviet arms supplies to
the Afghan army.
   He welcomed Perez de Cuellar's call Friday for a peaceful
settlement of the 10-year-old civil war but said it was ``not
enough.''
   The Afghan government hopes Perez de Cuellar will play ``a more
active and more serious role than he has played so far,'' Amani
said, noting he has been authorized to visit Kabul and Islamabad to
try to end the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
