<FIRST>r a AM-Computer-Soviets     08-05 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer-Soviets,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Bail for Three Charged In Soviet-Computer Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge denied bail to three foreign
businessmen accused in a scheme to sell sophisticated computer
equipment to the Soviet Union.
   U.S. District Judge Carolyn Dimmick said Friday there was a
significant risk that the men would try to flee the country.
   Shiv Mohan, 40, of New Delhi, India; David Whyte, 35, of
Mississauga, Ontario, and John Townsend, 43, a Briton living in New
Castle, Australia, were arrested July 21 in Buffalo, N.Y., on a
criminal complaint filed in U.S. District Court in Seattle.
   They were arrested as they met with Robert Casperson, the
president of C-Tek, a Kirkland, Wash., computer company, allegedly
to discuss diverting $900,000 in computer equipment through Canada
to the Soviet Union. Casperson was cooperating with federal agents.
   All three were charged with conspiring to export U.S.-made
computer equipment without a Commerce Department export license.
Mohan and Townsend also were charged with attempting to illegally
export a sophisticated computer to the Soviet Union.
   The Digital Equipment Corp. VAX 8700 super minicomputer that
federal agents say the men were trying to sell can be used to
design nuclear weapons, submarines and missile and radar tracking
systems.
   None of the equipment reached the Soviet Union.
