<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1653EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Baker     08-05 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Baker,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker, Brady, Thornburgh Visit Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III and
three other members of President Bush's Cabinet travel to Mexico
Sunday on a visit seen here as a milestone in recently improving
U.S.-Mexico relations.
   Mexican officials say they hope the meeting of the U.S.-Mexico
Binational Commission will ratify the ``spirit of Houston'' and
provide a platform for further progress.
   Aides say Bush and President Carlos Salinas de Gortari hit it
off well at a meeting in November in Houston, when both were
presidents-elect.
   The rank and size of the U.S. delegation alone are a good sign
for the meeting being held Sunday and Monday, high-ranking Mexican
officials said on condition their names not be disclosed.
   The commission has not met for 2{ years, although meetings were
supposed to be held every six months. Mexican and U.S. officials
blamed the lapse on an political emphasis last year on presidential
elections in both nations.
   Although relations between the Salinas and Bush administrations
are going well, similar honeymoon periods at the beginning of
recent Mexican presidencies have ended in bitterness, recrimination
and nationalist anger.
   ``In the past, we have sometimes had a dialogue of the deaf,''
said a top Salinas administration official.
   The United States is sending Baker, Attorney General Richard
Thornburgh, Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and Commerce
Secretary Robert A. Mosbacher.
   Other top officials include FBI director William Sessions, Drug
Enforcement Administration head John C. Lawn, Environmental
Protection Agency chief William Reilly and U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills.
   The Mexican delegation will be led by the Foreign Minister,
Fernando Solana, and five other Cabinet ministers, chief among them
Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe.
   The participants will discuss ``everything from border bridges
to the differences between our legal systems,'' said one Mexican
official.
   The top issues will be continuing foreign debt negotiations and
narcotics trafficking; other issues include immigration, trade and
investment, pollution and tourism.
   The meeting comes only two weeks after Mexico reached agreement
on reducing $53 billion of its debt to foreign banks. Brady and
other U.S. officials helped drive the bargain. Final details,
however, still must be worked out.
   The deal got a mixed reception in Mexico, with Salinas declaring
it a triumph and critics saying it didn't do enough.
   Salinas is trying to revive an economy hurt by six years of
austerity following the collapse of oil prices in 1982, and he has
argued that debt reduction is the only way to provide capital for
investment.
   He has liberalized trade laws and taken other steps to enourage
investment and exports, not just from the United States but also
from countries such as Japan and South Korea.
   Although U.S. officials have been pleased by many of Salinas'
actions, one said, ``They're not doing this to make us happy.
They're doing it because they think it will work.''
   One remaining rub is patent law, with U.S. companies complaining
that Mexican companies copy their products without compensation.
But even there, officials said, progress is being made.
   While Mexico got help on the debt, U.S. officials have been
effusive in their praise for Mexico's efforts to combat drug
trafficking. Salinas has cracked down hard, arresting top
traffickers and corrupt officials who had been untouchable for
years.
   Mexican officials still argue, however, that the real problem is
the demand for drugs in the United States.
   Mexicans also criticize the U.S. attitude towards Mexican
immigrants, who they say are taking jobs Americans are unable or
unwilling to fill.
   Salinas has run some political risks in appearing to accommodate
the United States on so many issues. Few Mexicans forget for long
that half of what was once Mexico was conquered or bought by the
United States.
   Although Mexico is now an urban society and the 13th largest
industrial nation in the world, the psychological problems of U.S.
condescension and Mexican sensitivity can still get in the way of
normal relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
