<DOCNO> AP890805-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1704EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bolivia     08-05 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Chooses Left-Leaning Candidate As Next President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress elected Jaime Paz Zamora
president early Saturday and the left-leaning former vice president
pledged to consolidate democracy and economic stability.
   In a telephone interview with The Associated Press after the
congressional vote, Paz Zamora said, ``I wish to express my
profound gratitude to the Bolivian people who, abiding by the
constitution, have expressed their will electing me president of
Bolivia.''
   He was elected by Congress because no candidate received a
majority in a May election.
   Paz Zamora, 50, a sociologist and leader of the
Social-Democratic Movement of the Revolutionary Left, will be sworn
in Sunday afternoon in the presence of five South American heads of
state, U.S. Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos and Prescott Bush,
brother of President Bush.
   Outgoing President Victor Paz Estenssoro, 82, will address a
joint session of Congress, ending a half-century political career
that includes four presidential terms.
   The new president, Paz Estenssoro's nephew, has said he will
maintain a free-market economy and welcome foreign investments
while giving special attention to improving the educational system
and health care. He met with U.S. Ambassador Robert Gelbard
Thursday and said he is particularly interested in investments in
the mining sector.
   In the May 7 presidential election, Paz Zamora came in third
with 19 percent. But in negotiations he gained the support of
former dictator Hugo Banzer Suarez who had finished second in the
balloting.
   The support of Banzer and his rightist party assured Paz Zamora
of victory in the congressional vote and he won with 98 of the 156
ballots.
   Under Bolivia's Constitution, if no candidate wins a majority in
the popular vote Congress elects the president by choosing from
among the top threet vote getters in the general election.
   Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada, the governing party's candidate,
received the most votes in the May 7 election with 24 percent, but
received only 49 votes in the congressional balloting. Banzer, a
former general, won 23 percent of the vote in the general election.
   Congress also elected lawyer Luis Ossio Sanjines, an ally of
Banzer and leader of the Christian Democratic Party, vice
president. Paz Zamora and Ossio Sanjines will serve four-year terms.
   Paz Zamora and Banzer, in forming the alliance, also agreed to
form a coalition government. Banzer's conservative Nationalist
Democratic Action Party will receive 10 Cabinet seats and Paz
Zamora's party seven.
   Their parties will share responsabilities in dealing with the
economy and Banzer will oversee a Supreme Council that is to
determine the government's overall policy.
   Banzer gained power in a coup in 1971 and ruled until 1978. In
1974, Paz Zamora was accused of plotting to overthrow Banzer's
government and he was jailed for six months and sent into exile.
   Banzer's decision Wednesday to back Paz Zamora for the
presidency surprised many Bolivians and led to a brief bank run
with thousands of people forming long lines at banks to withdraw
their deposits.
   Paz Zamora, once a Marxist, is considered now to be
left-of-center with ties to European Social Democratic parties.
   Cavazos, speaking to reporters upon his arrival Friday, said,
``President Bush looks forward to cooperating with the new Bolivian
administration in the many bilateral and international issues that
concern us.'' He said Bolivia has made progress with its economic
program ``which has become a model for other nations gripped by
hyperinflation and crippled by economic instability.''
   Paz Zamora inherits an economy that five years ago had an
inflation rate of 24,000 percent but is now running at an annual
rate of 6 percent.
   Sunday's swearing in ceremony will install Bolivia's 76th
government since the country became independent from Spain in 1825.
The inauguration will be the first time in 25 years that a
government completed its term and relinquished power to a
democratically elected successor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
