<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Soviet-Gold     08-05 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet-Gold,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Cleaning Dirty River Strike Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of Nizhny Tagilsk, a steel town in the
Ural Mountains, are accustomed to area rivers running black and
brown from industrial residue.
   The Tass news agency reported Saturday that some municipal
workers volunteered to try to clean one of the most polluted rivers
and were surprised when they found flakes of yellow metal in the
grime.
   Scientists confirmed the flakes were gold and the workers
combined panning and cleaning.
   Tass said the workers collected 11 pounds of gold from about a
mile of the river and the metal was sold by city officials for
$59,000. The agency reported the money was used to buy medical
equipment for the city.
   Nizhny Tagilsk, 550 miles east of Moscow, has a reputation of
being one of the most polluted cities in the Soviet Union, even
abandoned by the ravens that once settled there. But with the
degree of gold panning under way its rivers may get cleaner.
