<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1825EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     08-05 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rail Workers Stop Trains in Pay Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rail workers in southwestern Poland
stopped trains for an hour Saturday in their latest bid to pressure
the government for pay increases to counter triple-digit inflation.
   The rail stoppage came as new Prime Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak
met with economic and political specialists from the opposition
Solidarity movement in an effort to assemble a Cabinet.
   Former Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, now first
secretary of the Communist Party, conferred with party and army
leaders Saturday, urging them to be proud of the party and defend
it from ``demagogic attacks.''
   Rakowski told the army officers meeting in Warsaw that in the
past the armed forces served as ``a strong support of people's
rule. The situation is the same today and I believe it will
continue in the future.''
   The rail stoppage between noon and 1 p.m. affected domestic rail
traffic in the Silesia region except for certain trains taking
children to summer camps, according to reports in the official
media and from the Solidarity Information Service.
   State television said about 80 trains were stopped.
   The strike was supported both by Solidarity and the official
communist-allied trade unions.
   Jan Renda, leader of a strike committee in Katowice, said rail
workers now receive $60 a month in basic pay plus overtime and
various differentials and bonuses.
   The workers want the basic pay increased to $96 a month along
with cost-of-living adjustments recently approved by Parliament.
   Management is offering to raise the basic pay to $84, but that
would include a cost-of-living adjustment that has not yet been
computed, state television reported.
   The average monthly income in Poland is $127, according to
government statistics.
   Renda, interviewed on state television, said, ``If our demands
are not met, we expect the worse _ a general (railway) strike _
something that has never happened in the postwar period.''
   Solidarity and the government media reported strikes by postal
workers in Legnica, by workers at a tire factory in Gruzdiaz and by
tram-car operators in Walbrzych.
   Strikes for higher pay have become common as the cost of living
increases steadily. It is estimated the inflation rate for this
year will exceed 120 percent.
   Gen. Kiszczak, who was turned down Thursday when he asked
Solidarity Sen. Zofia Kuratowska to join his government, continued
meetings with Solidarity lawmakers.
   Kiszczak met Saturday with Solidarity Deputy Ryszard Bugaj and
opposition political theorists Bronislaw Geremek and Deputy Jacek
Kuron.
</TEXT>
