<DOCNO> AP890805-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 1836EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-PublicHousing     08-05 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Public Housing,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Blasts HUD, Dallas in Public Housing Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge, in a ruling that lambasted city
and federal housing officials, said Dallas helped create a
segregated public housing system and must help pay to dismantle it.
   In his ruling Friday, U.S. District Judge Jerry Buchmeyer
blasted the federal Department of Housing and Urban Development,
the city and the Dallas Housing Authority for what he called a
``long, unbroken history'' of segregation in housing.
   Buchmeyer accused the three of deliberately disrupting plans to
correct the problem, and said he would appoint a special master to
monitor compliance of a 1987 consent agreement handled in his court.
   ``The undisputed facts establish that the city was a substantial
cause of deliberate racial segregation and discrimination in its
public housing programs,'' Buchmeyer said.
   His ruling added the city to the list of defendants in a
4-year-old desegregation case against the housing authority and
HUD. He said he would rule later what financial share the city
would assume.
   Seven black women sued in 1985, contending that thousands of
federally assisted apartments in Dallas were segregated by race and
unequal in conditions because of a longstanding pattern of
discrimination by HUD and the city housing authority.
   The judge approved a settlement in January 1987 requiring
demolition of most of the dilapidated West Dallas housing project
and relocation of tenants to private, rent-subsidized apartments
throughout Dallas and the suburbs.
   Another part of his Friday ruling could have the effect of
freeing up an estimated $3 million in federal funds for the
demolitions. The funds were frozen by an amendment written by a
Texas congressman to a HUD appropriations bill.
   Buchmeyer found that Mayor Annette Strauss and other city
officials have chosen to ignore the 1987 decree.
   Attorneys for the plaintiffs said Buchmeyer's ruling would lead
to improvements for thousands of poor families living in federally
financed slums.
   ``It's the first time a city has been ordered to join with a
housing authority to desegregate its housing,'' said attorney Mike
Daniel. ``And it's the first time a city has been ordered to fund
the remedies for the separate and unequal conditions it helped
create.''
   ``It's fantastic,'' said Mary Dews, one of the plaintiffs in the
case who has lived in subsidized housing for 20 years.
   ``There's a lot of people who say racism doesn't exist in
Dallas, but this shows that it does,'' she said.
   Mrs. Strauss, contacted Friday while vacationing in California,
would not comment on the ruling on the advice of the city attorney
until the city council could be briefed.
   ``We have to hear what the attorney will recommend,'' Mrs.
Strauss said. ``Until we know that, we don't do anything.''
   Assistant City Attorney Donald Postell declined to comment, as
did attorneys for the housing authority and HUD.
   Buchmeyer ruled unconstitutional a 1988 amendment by U.S. Rep.
Martin Frost, D-Texas. It prohibits use of federal money for
demolition of any of the nearly 3,500 apartments at the West Dallas
project.
   Under the court-approved settlement, 839 apartments in the West
Dallas project were to be renovated and the rest demolished.
Residents could seek alternate, privately owned housing with
federal rent-subsidy certificates. The cost of the demolition was
estimated at $20,000 per unit.
   Buchmeyer said the Frost Amendment was unconstitutional because
it violated separation of powers.
   Frost said he felt the housing should be renovated rather than
razed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
