<SECOND>AM-Irish Protest,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>46 Arrested in Rally Demanding British Troops Leave Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 demonstrators marched Saturday
demanding the withdrawal of British troops from Northern Ireland,
and police said 46 people were arrested when right-wing opponents
confronted the marchers.
   Police moved in as a group from the right-wing British National
Party made their way to the march in north London, which was
organized by the Irish Freedom Movement in advance of the 20th
anniversary on Aug. 14 of the deployment of British troops in the
province.
   The British National Party staged a counterdemonstration in
central London, and a group of marchers later went to the Irish
march, police said.
   A Scotland Yard spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said 39 of those arrested were from the right-wing march and seven
were from the Irish march.
   British troops were deployed into the mainly Protestant province
to control sectarian fighting. The mainly Roman Catholic Irish
Republican Army is fighting to drive the British force from the
province and unite it with Ireland.
