<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     08-05 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas woman says the Lone Star State's
official mammal and unofficial roadside distraction _ the armadillo
_ could solve a flap over license plates.
   Margaret Knox told the Texas Highway Commission that it should
dump plans to put ``The Friendship State'' on Texas license plates
and choose instead plates shaped like armadillos.
   Between the numbers and letters on the plate would be a star,
representing Texas' standing as the Lone Star state.
   ``I think it's very realistic. It would be real neat,'' Mrs.
Knox, 64, said Saturday.
   Since unveiling the design for ``The Friendship State'' plate
last month, the highway department has been flooded with complaints
from people saying the slogan doesn't fit the spirit of Texas.
Politicians have entered the controversy, saying the slogan is
wimpy.
   ``If you have to advertise that you're friendly, forget it,''
Mrs. Knox said. ``I think it's terrible.''
   She got the idea for the armadillo plate six years ago on a
Canadian trip when she saw a license plate for the Northwest
Territories shaped like a polar bear. ``It was striking,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Between the baby bottle and the brown
bag, there were lunch boxes.
   ``They were the first status symbols,'' said Scott Bruce, 34,
who has stirred the interest of baby boomers with a string of
enterprises celebrating that old schoolyard standard in all its
glorious incarnations.
   That Barbie doll box bought at the dime store for $3.49 back
somewhere in the mid-1970s can fetch hundreds of dollars at auction
these days. Bruce collects and resells them.
   The Beatles, the Jetsons, Mickey Mouse, Howdy Doody and even
yesteryear's teen idol, Bobby Sherman, are also among the blue-chip
boxes most highly prized by people generally between the age of 25
and 40, Bruce said.
   About 120 million lunch boxes were sold in their heyday between
1950 and 1970. So, according to Bruce's calculations, every baby
boomer carried at least one, sometimes two, to school each year.
   ``By the end of the 1950s there were four competing lunchbox
companies,'' Bruce said. ``Kids had a choice of models that
reflected their personalities, sort of like an automobile
showroom.''
   Now lunch boxes are available only in plastic. The last steel
version, featuring Rambo, was pressed in 1987, phasing out the
metal models more than a decade after a mother whose son got struck
in the head with one brought and won a lawsuit banning them in
Florida.
   Bruce saw the ban coming. He knew it was only a matter of time
before baby boomers in search of nostalgia created a demand.
   He spent about $10,000 on his entire collection of 1,500 boxes
and thermoses, a fifth of which he recently auctioned for $17,000.
</TEXT>
