<FIRST>r a AM-PowerOutage-Riot     08-05 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Power Outage-Riot,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outage Sparks Fights, Rowdiness At Beach Resort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEASIDE HEIGHTS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting broke out among a crowd of
thousands on this beach resort's mile-long boardwalk after a power
outage left the area in darkness, authorities said.
   ``The lights flickered and everybody went crazy,'' said Eric
Slavin, manager of Lucky's Towels on the boardwalk. ``People
started kicking down garbage cans, people were yelling and
screaming and egging it on.''
   People smashed windows, overturned garbage cans and began
fighting after the lights went out around 1 a.m. Saturday, police
said.
   About 25 people were arrested, most for misdemeanors such as
fighting and disturbing the peace, said Mayor George Tompkins.
   More than 200 police officers and 14 police dogs from 45
departments arrived on the scene, said Borough Police Capt. Gerald
LaStella.
   Police blocked the bridge leading to the island community and
evacuated people from the boardwalk.
   ``There were kids running around throwing bottles, knocking over
garbage cans and some attempted to steal some things from the
stands,'' said LaStella.
   No injuries were reported, police said. Water and sewer service
was maintained by back-up generators.
   ``The boardwalk was full and the nightclubs were full. It wasn't
rioting, it was fighting,'' said Tompkins, who added that damage
was minor.
   Some people were stuck on amusement rides, but police helped
them off, he said.
   Order was restored about 3 a.m., Tompkins said.
   LaStella said up to 25,000 people were on the boardwalk at the
time of the power failure. Some merchants said the figure was
closer to 6,000. Officials say the small community, which has a
year-round population of about 2,100, swells to about 100,000
people on summer weekends.
   The outage occurred when a substation transformer of the Jersey
Central Power &amp; Light Co. failed, said a company spokesman, James
F. Lowney.
   He expected power to be restored Saturday evening.
</TEXT>
