<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 2005EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary-Election     08-05 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Election,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Wins Two of Three Seats in By-Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition candidates won two of three
seats contested for Parliament in multiparty elections Saturday,
state television reported.
   In the third by-election race, the required number of voters did
not participate and another election will be held.
   Although only three of 387 parliamentary seats were contested,
the poor showing by the Communist Party was considered an
indication of voter sentiment before national multiparty elections
planned for June.
   Low voter turnouts and the failure of a candidate to win a
majority in by-elections on July 5 led to Saturday's round. By law,
a turnout of more than 50 percent is mandatory and the winner must
receive a majority of the votes cast.
   Less than 50 percent of the eligible voters turned out for the
election at Kiskunfelegyhaza and another round will have to be
scheduled, state television reported.
   The two winners were Ernoe Raffay in Szeged and Jozsef Debreceni
in Kecskemet. They were backed by the Hungarian Democratic Forum,
an alliance of political groups opposed to the ruling Communists.
   Raffay, a historian, defeated Karoly Miklos, a bus company
manager who was the candidate of the Communists' reform wing, and
Levente Dobozy, an independent. Raffay received 61.8 percent of the
votes, Miklos 22.5 percent and Dobozy 16 percent.
   Debreceni ran unopposed after the Communist candidate and
another rival dropped out following poor showings in the July 5
balloting.
   The evening newscast said Debreceni won 70 percent of the vote
but did not account for the remaining 30 percent.
   The report said 57 percent of the electorate cast ballots in
Kecskemet but did not give the turnout in the two other races.
   Leaders of the Communist Party made campaign appearances last
week to help the party's candidates _ with little success.
   At a rally in Kecskemet Wednesday, party chairman Rezsoe Nyers
said that although the elections would not determine the country's
political future, they could not be ignored because they marked the
beginning of a multiparty election system.
   Lutheran clergyman Gabor Roszik won 69.2 percent of the votes in
the July 5 by-election in Goedoelloe. He is considered to be the
first opposition figure to be elected to the National Assembly
since 1947, when the last completely free elections were held.
   Some non-communists won seats in 1985 under limited
multiple-candidate elections but all candidates had to have the
endorsement of the Communist-run Patriotic People's Front. That
stipulation has been removed.
</TEXT>
