<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Money     08-05 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Money,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>New 50,000 Cordova Bill to Circulate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua will put a new
50,000-cordoba bill into circulation in an effort to keep up with
steady devaluations and five-digit inflation that has forced some
residents to carry bundles of money.
   Newspapers said Saturday that the new bill, worth about $2.50,
will begin circulated Monday.
   The announcement comes less than four months after the
government introduced the 20,000-cordoba note, the highest bill now
in circulation.
   Since the beginning of the year, the cordoba has dropped from an
official rate of 2,000 to the dollar to 20,000 to the dollar. The
last devaluation was in June, when it fell from 9,500 to its
current rate.
   Under a government austerity program this year, inflation has
dropped from a rate of 20,000 for 1988. The rate for the month of
July was 8.5 percent, according to official figures.
   However, prices on numerous basic products, including beans,
cooking oil and soft drinks have increased substantially in the
past few days.
   The new note carries the picture of Jose Dolores Estrada,
considered a national hero for his defeat of American adventurers
Byron Cole and William Walker and their militias on Sept. 14, 1856.
   On the reverse side, is the Hacienda San Jacinto, the scene of
the defeat.
</TEXT>
