<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 2117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BigBurger     08-05 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Big Burger,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Claims Hamburger Record With Patty for 10,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEYMOUR, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This farm town, which claims it invented
the hamburger, fried up a 5,520-pound patty Saturday and served it
to about 10,000 people in a bid for a spot in the Guinness Book of
World Records.
   ``It was nice and juicy,'' said Doris Witbrow of Suamico.
   The event at the Outagamie County Fairgrounds was a tribute to
Charles ``Hamburger Charlie'' Nagreen, who _ according to local
historians _ mashed a meatball to make the world's first hamburger
in 1885.
   About 50 cooks in aprons worked around a specially designed
grill 21 feet in diameter and heated by 12 gas burners. It took
about two hours to cook the 6-inch-thick layer of ground chuck.
   To avoid having to flip the patty, grill designers Steve Mielke
and Joe Sauer used a cover to cook both sides at once. A
truck-mounted crane lifted the cover into place and suspended Sauer
over the patty as he sprinkled salt.
   The burger was intended to serve 15,000 people, but the meat ran
out after an hour and 45 minutes and 10,000 diners. Five thousand
buns were left over.
   Seymour plans to submit its claim to the biggest burger to
publishers of the Guinness Book.
   According to the Guinness Book, the largest hamburger on record
weighed 5,005 pounds, 13.8 ounces and was cooked in Cape Town,
South Africa.
   Seymour, a town of 2,600 people 15 miles west of Green Bay,
disputes claims by other communities, including Hamburg, N.Y., to
making the first burger.
   According to local lore, the 15-year-old Nagreen was selling
meatballs from a booth at a fair when it occurred to him that
people could carry them more easily if the meat were flattened
between two slices of bread.
   The Appleton storekeeper died in 1951 after 65 years of hawking
hamburgers at county fairs.
   The grill used to cook Saturday's giant hamburger was bigger
than the patty, leaving space for a bigger attempt next year, said
Carl Kuehne, whose Green Bay Dressed Beef donated the meat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
