<FIRST>u i AM-Japan     08-05 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidate Says He's Determined to Revive Scandal-Plagued Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The race to be Japan's prime minister started in
earnest Saturday with front-running Toshiki Kaifu, joined by the
two other candidates on television, saying he was ``young,
energetic'' and determined to revive his scandal-plagued party.
   On Tuesday, the governing Liberal Democratic Party will elect a
new leader to become Japan's third prime minister this year. When
the nominations deadline passed on Saturday, there were three
candidates, none of them well-known or possessing a personal power
base.
   Kaifu, 58, is a former education minister whom analysts see as
strongly leading because he is backed by large factions in the
party.
   The other two candidates are Yoshiro Hayashi, 62, a former
welfare minister who called for more open politics, and Shintaro
Ishihara, 56, a former transport minister who comes from the
party's nationalist wing.
   One of them will replace Prime Minister Sousuke Uno, who is
resigning to take responsibility for the party's crushing defeat
July 23 in elections for the upper house of Parliament. Uno took
office June 2, succeeding Noboru Takeshita, who resigned in the
Recruit bribery scandal that has tainted most of the leaders of the
party.
   ``I am young, energetic and have power to act,'' Kaifu said in
an 80-minute televised news conference at which the three
candidates answered questions prepared in advance.
   They all said they favor party political reforms, continuing
Japan's ban on rice imports and reviewing the new 3 percent sales
tax that was a major factor in the party's steep decline in
popularity.
   They did not attack each other openly, instead often saying they
shared the previous speaker's opinion.
   Hayashi came close to attacking the front-runner by saying the
party's decision-making should become more ``easy to understand''
to win back the voters' trust. Hayashi's candidacy emerged after it
seemed there might be only one in the race _ Kaifu, the nominee put
forward by a combination of big factions.
   The party's 405 members of Parliament and 47 local
representatives vote in a secret ballot on Tuesday to elect a new
president.
   The party leader will be confirmed as prime minister Wednesday
on the strength of the Liberal Democrats' majority in the lower
house of Parliament, which chooses the head of government.
   But since the party lost its upper-house majority in the recent
election, the Liberal Democrats may face the embarrassment for the
first time of a Socialist-led majority in the upper house refusing
to endorse the winner from the lower house.
   While Hayashi said he was clear of any link to the Recruit Co.
conglomerate that is accused of trying to bribe politicians and
others, Kaifu has confirmed he received about $110,000 in legal
donations from Recruit over five years.
   Ishihara said Recruit had purchased $21,700 worth of tickets to
symposiums he organized. The money was returned to Recruit after
the scandal emerged, he said.
   Asked at the news conference about trade tension with the United
States, Ishihara said Japan should reject unreasonable U.S. demands
and blaming ``a lack of competitiveness in U.S. products'' for the
trade imbalance.
   Ishihara also attacked the government for agreeing to U.S.
demands to revise the agreement on joint production of a new
fighter plane for the Japanese air force. Japan could have built
the fighter itself, Ishihara said: ``Why should we accept such a
deal?''
</TEXT>
