<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 2227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Mafia     08-05 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Mafia,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Suspicious' Phone Line in Mafia Investigator's Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators found an ``irregular'' wire
attached to the telephone of Italy's top Mafia investigator, and
newspapers said Saturday his phone had been tapped.
   Interior Ministry technicians discovered the wire after four
days of searching the office of Giovanni Falcone, a magistrate who
has provided key information in U.S. Mafia cases and has become a
symbol of Italy's war on the crime syndicate.
   Newspapers speculated that the purported phone tap had provided
information used in an assassination attempt against Falcone in
June.
   ``At the moment, we have only confirmed a suspicious situation,
an irregular wire that parts from the line and ends at a telephone
switchboard,'' Police Commissioner Ferdinando Masone said Saturday.
   He denied reports that a tiny tape recorder had been found near
the phone.
   The Rome-based daily La Repubblica said investigators also
discovered that someone had opened the phone outlets in Falcone's
office and tinkered with the machinery.
   The reports of phone-tapping came a day after Premier Giulio
Andreotti told Parliament that organized crime had become ``a true
national emergency'' and proposed giving increased powers to state
security agents.
   Police have been examining how assailants learned Falcone's
schedule on June 20 and set up a bag of explosives in the water in
which he planned to take a swim. Security guards spotted the
waterproof bag in time.
   Falcone won fame for his work with an aggressive anti-Mafia
group of magistrates. He persuaded mob figure Tommasso Buscetta to
testify, a breakthrough that led to a major organized crime trial
resulting in the conviction of 338 people in 1987.
</TEXT>
