<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 2237EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CollegeDesegregation     08-05 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-College Desegregation,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Refuses to Stop Desegregation for Colleges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-judge federal panel has refused
to stop the establishment of a single governing board for
Louisiana's 17 colleges, the key part of a court-ordered
desegregation plan.
   ``It is high time that higher education in Louisiana be reworked
at all levels in a unified effort to improve the education offered
in this state to all Louisiana citizens,'' the court said Friday in
an opinion issued in New Orleans.
   The panel last month ordered Louisiana to replace four governing
boards with one in a package of sweeping reforms to desegragate the
state's 17 public colleges and universities.
   The judges ruled the present system ``has perpetuated illegal
segregation.''
   The ruling came in a lawsuit filed 15 years ago by the U.S.
Justice Department.
   Currently, one board governs the Lousiana State University
system, another governs the mostly black Southern University system
and a third governs the others. All three boards answer to the
State Board of Regents for Higher Education.
   State Attorney General William Guste, who had asked to court to
overturn its decision mandating the single board, said he would
appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   In a motion filed in New Orleans on Thursday, Guste said the
state Constitution calls for four governing boards and the federal
court ``can't change the state constitution unless it is patently
unconstitutional.''
   The new board has been ordered to restructure the higher
education system beginning Aug. 18.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer has appointed the board's 17 members, and
Senate confirmation hearings are scheduled to begin Aug. 14.
   The court on Friday also rejected a request by the Southern
University Board of Supervisors, the Justice Department and the
Grambling State University Alumni Association to put in the ruling
specific amounts the state must spend to improve programs at
predominantly black Southern and Grambling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
