<FIRST>r a AM-ABAConvention     08-05 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABA Convention,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers Debate Abortion Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of American women who have had
abortions will be urged to join the national debate on the issue
when the U.S. Supreme Court takes it up again this fall, an
attorney told fellow lawyers Saturday.
   Women will not return ``to a form of enslavement'' caused by
making abortion illegal, Margie Pitts Hames, an Atlanta attorney
who handles abortion-related matters, said during a panel
discussion of abortion at the American Bar Association's annual
convention.
   Hames said groups around the country are working to mobilize the
25 million women who have had legal abortions in the United States.
   A standing-room-only crowd of about 150 people, mostly women,
attended the debate by four attorneys, two Hawaii legislators, a
journalist and a historian.
   In a ruling last month, the Supreme Court issued a ruling
allowing states to restrict abortions.
   Panelists agreed that the ruling signaled dramatic changes in
abortion rights and regulations, but could not agree what those
changes were.
   Hames said the public debate would be shifted as women and their
partners spoke up to demand a right to make their own decisions.
   However, Paige Comstock Cunningham, staff counsel for Americans
United for Life, said Americans are rethinking their sense of
morality on two issues: ``What is wrong with the world now and what
do we want the world to look like?''
</TEXT>
