<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--AspirinSuit     08-05 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Aspirin Suit,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Rejects Parents' Arguments In $50 Million Suit Against Aspirin
Makers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OROVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents whose young son apparently
suffered brain damage after taking aspirin six years ago on Friday
lost their $50 million lawsuit against two drug companies and two
distributors.
   A Superior Court jury said the apparent injury to Larry A. Bunch
Jr. could not be linked to aspirin he took in 1983 at age 9 when he
had chicken pox.
   Shortly after taking the aspirin, the boy became seriously ill
and slipped into a coma. He regained consciousness, but apparently
suffered brain damage, according to medical testimony in the
monthlong trial.
   Parents Larry and Isabel Bunch sued Sterling Drug Co., the maker
of Bayer Aspirin; Rawson Drug and Sundry Co., which manufactures a
generic aspirin; and distributors Whitworth Inc. and Norwich-Eaton
Pharmaceuticals.
   The parents' attorney, Robert Davis, said he hadn't decided
whether to appeal the decision.
   Reye's syndrome, which causes liver and brain inflammation, has
been linked to aspirin. Defense attorneys argued successfully that
the boy suffered from hepatitis or encephalitis not caused by
aspirin.
</TEXT>
