<FILEID>AP-NR-08-05-89 0652EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv05-06 1stLd-Writethru 08-05 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Week's Business, Adv 05-06, 1st Ld-Writethru,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions Aug. 5-6</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Week That Would Make Edward G. Robinson Proud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restransmitting to fix release date at the bottom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The word racketeer has acquired some new meaning
in the high-living financial world, and it's not a name for the guy
who strings tennis rackets at the country club.
   To a half-dozen securities professionals convicted in New York
and 46 futures traders indicted in Chicago under a tough law aimed
at fighting organized crime, ``racketeer'' is like the ghost of Al
Capone, a stigma that could plague them for the rest of their lives.
   If anyone in the lucrative business of buying and selling
stocks, bonds and commodities still had any illusion they were
somehow exempt from prosecution under this law, they likely were
sobered by the events of this past week.
   Of particular significance were the New York convictions in the
so-called Princeton-Newport case, based on what many attorneys had
called confused and even flimsy evidence of fraud.
   This showed with dramatic certainty that juries will convict
Wall Streeters under the racketeering law. It's an ominous sign for
similar defendants facing trial, especially Michael Milken, the
ex-junk bond trader for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. who faces far
more serious charges.
   The Princeton-Newport case concerned a now-dissolved investment
firm called Princeton-Newport Partners. Five of its members and
another ex-Drexel trader were accused of creating phony tax losses
via prearranged securities trades.
   Two days after the Princeton-Newport verdicts, prosecutors in
Chicago announced long-awaited indictments stemming from a lengthy
undercover probe of alleged fraud in the world's largest
commodities markets.
   Again using the racketeering law, prosecutors accused the 46
defendants of turning the trading pits into their own private clubs
where they reserved the best deals for themselves and tossed the
dregs to unsuspecting clients.
   Both the Chicago and New York prosecutions represent an
aggressive application of the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organization Act or RICO, as it's commonly called. It was enacted
by Congress nearly two decades ago to combat gangsters.
   The law is considered one of the most powerful enforcement tools
ever enacted in this country, enabling prosecutors to seize a
suspect's assets before trial and providing for crippling fines and
lengthy prison terms upon conviction.
   Despite criticism from many lawyers that the law is excessive,
its application has expanded over the years to prosecutions of
criminal defendants ranging from union bosses to motorcycle gangs
to politicians.
   The RICO acronym, also the name of the Capone-like mobster
played by Edward G. Robinson in the 1930 film ``Little Caesar,''
was coined by one of the law's authors, G. Robert Blakey, a Notre
Dame law professor.
   ``RICO means crime is called by its correct name,'' Blakey once
said. ``If people are running a racket, why shouldn't we try them
for being a racketeer?''
   In other business and economic news this past week:
   _Convoluted economic reports sent confusing signals into the
financial markets. The Commerce Department said its chief
forecasting gauge fell 0.1 percent in June, the fourth drop in five
months and a strong signal of a slowdown. But the Labor Department
said unemployment dropped in July, suggesting the economy is
growing stronger.
   _Alleged sleazy business practices hurt the reputations of the
nation's largest drug chain, charge-card company and home-shopping
network. Rite Aid Corp. and its president were indicted on charges
they tried to bribe an Ohio regulator. A top executive at American
Express Co. resigned for his role in trying to discredit a rival
international banker through a smear campaign. Home Shopping
Network Inc. was slammed with a $100 million defamation verdict for
falsely claiming GTE Corp. telephone mismanagement hurt its sales.
   _In the takeover business, investor Irwin Jacobs knocked on Avon
Products Co.'s door with a $2.85 billion offer but the cosmetic
giant rejected it; and Amax Inc. agreed to buy Canada's
Falconbridge Ltd., in a $2.4 billion deal that would create one of
the world's largest metal producers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for weekend editions Aug. 5-6</NOTE>
</DOC>
